text: Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 31a (DEE31) is a type of autosomal dominant disease characterized by onset in the first months or years of life of refractory seizures and global developmental delay from early infancy that has material basis in heterozygous mutation in the DNM1 gene on chromosome 9q34. It is also known as DEE31A, early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 31, and has the exact synonyms of DEE31, DEE31A, developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 31, and early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 31.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 5 (DEE5) is a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by global developmental delay and the onset in the first months of life of tonic seizures or infantile spasms, which has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the SPTAN1 gene on chromosome 9q34. It's also known as DEE5 and early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 5.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 14 (DEE 14) is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects brain development. It is characterized by refractory focal seizures developing by six months of age and the arrest of psychomotor development. The condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the KCNT1 gene on chromosome 9q34. This disorder has an exact synonym, early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 14.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 3 (DEE3) is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by onset in the first months of life of erratic, typically myoclonic, refractory seizures that have a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SLC25A22 gene on chromosome 11p15. It has an exact synonym of early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 3 (EIEE3).

DEE49 is a type of autosomal recessive developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. It is characterized by neonatal onset seizures, global developmental delay with intellectual disability and lack of speech, hypotonia, spasticity, and coarse facial features that have a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the DENND5A gene located on chromosome 11p15. The condition is also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 49, and it has an exact synonym of DEE49.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 41 (DEE41) is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects brain development in infants. It is characterized by severe psychomotor impairment, seizures, and abnormal brain structure such as delayed myelination, thin corpus callosum, and cerebral atrophy. The condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the SLC1A2 gene on chromosome 11p13. It is also known by its exact synonym DEE41 or early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 41.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 29 (DEE29) is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which means that it is passed down through families and can affect people who have not inherited the gene from either parent. It is characterized by onset in the first months of life of refractory myoclonic seizures, poor overall growth, congenital microcephaly with cerebral atrophy and impaired myelination on brain imaging, spasticity with abnormal movements, peripheral neuropathy, and poor visual fixation. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the AARS1 gene on chromosome 16q22. The exact synonyms for DEE29 are developmental and epileptic encephalopathy, early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 29.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 42 is a type of autosomal dominant disease. Microcephaly, seizures, and developmental delay is a condition that affects brain development and can cause problems with a child's growth, movement, and cognitive abilities. Pustular psoriasis 14, also known as acrodermatitis continua of Hallopeau, is a type of psoriasis characterized by sudden, repeated episodes of high-grade fever, generalized rash, and disseminated pustules, with hyperleukocytosis and elevated serum levels of C-reactive protein. It has a genetic basis, specifically due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the IL36RN gene on chromosome 2q14.

This form of psoriasis is different from other types in that it presents with acute and chronic phases. During the acute phase, patients may experience a fever along with skin lesions such as pustules, while during the chronic phase, skin dryness and scaling can be seen. The exact cause of this form of psoriasis is not yet fully understood, but research continues to shed light on its genetic basis.

It's important to note that acrodermatitis continua of Hallopeau is not the same as deficiency of IL-36R antagonist, which refers to a different condition with distinct symptoms and causes.

Psoriasis 2, also known as plaque-type psoriasis, is a common form of psoriasis that affects approximately 80% to 90% of people with the condition. It typically presents as elevated, red patches covered in white scales called silver flakes. These patches can range from small to large and may join together to form larger areas of thickened skin. Psoriasis 2 has a strong genetic component, with research suggesting that individuals who inherit a specific combination of genes are more likely to develop the condition. One such gene is CARD14, which is located on chromosome 17q25. A heterozygous mutation in this gene may increase the risk of developing psoriasis 2, although other factors, such as exposure to certain triggers and environmental conditions, also play a role in its development.

Peroxisome biogenesis disorder 1a, also known as Zellweger syndrome, is a rare genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to produce peroxisomes. These small organelles are essential for various metabolic processes, particularly in the liver and kidney.

Peroxisome biogenesis disorder 1a occurs due to mutations in the PEX1 gene, which is located on chromosome 7q21. When an individual has two copies of the faulty gene (homozygous) or a combination of one faulty gene and one working gene (compound heterozygous), it can lead to the development of this disorder.

The symptoms of peroxisome biogenesis disorder 1a are varied, depending on which organs are affected. Some common symptoms include liver disease, neurological problems, hearing and vision loss, and kidney dysfunction. The severity of the condition can range from mild to life-threatening, and there is currently no cure for this disorder.

However, early diagnosis and intervention can help manage the symptoms and improve quality of life. Treatment typically involves a combination of medications, nutritional support, and specialized care from healthcare professionals experienced in managing rare genetic disorders like peroxisome biogenesis disorder 1a.

Peroxisome biogenesis disorder 2a, also known as Zellweger Syndrome, is a rare genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to produce peroxisomes. Peroxisomes are small organelles found in all cells that play a vital role in breaking down fats and other lipids. When these organelles are not functioning properly, it can lead to a build-up of fatty substances in the liver, spleen, kidneys, and brain. This can cause severe developmental delays, physical abnormalities, and even death if left untreated.
Peroxisome biogenesis disorder 2a is caused by mutations in the PEX5 gene on chromosome 12p13. With homozygous mutation of this gene, the body cannot produce enough functional peroxisomes and as a result, the accumulation of fatty substances occurs. This disorder can affect multiple organ systems including the liver, spleen, kidneys, lungs, and brain.
Treatment for Peroxisome Biogenesis Disorder 2a typically involves enzyme replacement therapy using large quantities of the missing enzyme. In addition, dietary modifications may also be necessary to help manage symptoms related to fatty substance build-up in organs and tissues.
Overall, Peroxisome Biogenesis Disorder 2a is a complex and life-threatening condition that requires comprehensive management strategies to support the affected individual's health and well-being.

Peroxisome biogenesis disorder 3a, also known as Zellweger syndrome, is a rare genetic disorder that affects the normal development of peroxisomes in cells. It is caused by mutations in the PEX12 gene on chromosome 17. The exact synonym for this condition is peroxisome biogenesis disorder 3A.

Peroxisome biogenesis disorder 4a, also known as Zellweger syndrome, is a rare genetic disorder that affects the function of peroxisomes in the body. It occurs due to mutations in the PEX6 gene on chromosome 6p21.1 and can be inherited in an autosomal recessive manner or sporadically.

Peroxisome biogenesis disorder 4a mainly affects infants, causing a wide range of symptoms such as developmental delays, vision problems, feeding difficulties, liver disease, and intellectual disability. The severity of the symptoms can vary greatly among affected individuals. Treatment options are limited and primarily focus on managing the symptoms and providing support to the patient and their family.

It is important for those with Zellweger syndrome or suspected of having the condition to receive proper medical care from a team of specialists, including genetic counselors, pediatricians, metabolic specialists, and other healthcare professionals experienced in managing rare genetic disorders.

mucolipidosis is a condition in which the body has difficulty breaking down and utilizing fats. This leads to an excessive buildup of fat, carbohydrates, and other substances in various tissues of the body. It can cause a variety of symptoms, including poor growth, developmental delays, and organ dysfunction. Mucolipidosis is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the gene for the condition to develop. Treatment options may include dietary restrictions, enzyme replacement therapy, and other supportive care measures.

Gangliosidosis type 3, also known as adult-onset GM1 gangliosidosis, is a rare genetic disorder characterized by neurodegeneration and mild skeletal changes. It has an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the defective gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition. The age at onset can range from 3 to 30 years, with symptoms typically appearing later in life compared to other forms of GM1 gangliosidosis. It is caused by a deficiency in the enzyme beta-hexosaminidase A, which leads to the accumulation of GM1 ganglioside in the body. Treatment options may include enzyme replacement therapy and supportive care to manage symptoms, although there is currently no cure for this disorder.

Mucolipidosis type IV, also known as Wolcott's Mucolipidosis, is a genetic disorder characterized by the accumulation of abnormal lipoprotein complexes in the lysosome. These complexes consist mainly of lipids and proteins that are unable to be degraded and can cause damage to various organs, particularly affecting the eyes, brain, heart, and lungs.
Symptoms usually appear during infancy or early childhood and can include developmental delays, vision impairment, seizures, and growth retardation. Over time, these symptoms worsen as the lipoprotein complexes continue to accumulate. Currently, there is no cure for Mucolipidosis Type IV, but early diagnosis and treatment can help manage its effects and improve quality of life.

That's correct! Cerebral cavernous malformation 1, also known as CCM1 or KRIT1-related cerebral cavernous malformation, is a type of cerebral cavernous malformation. It is characterized by the presence of abnormal blood vessels in the brain that can cause symptoms such as headache, seizure, and hemorrhage. The KRIT1 gene on chromosome 7q21 plays a crucial role in the development and function of these blood vessels, and mutations in this gene can lead to the formation of cerebral cavernous malformations, including CCM1.

Leukocyte adhesion deficiency 2 (LAD-2) is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the absence of Sialyl Lewis X (sLe(x)) on the surface of white blood cells, specifically on the E-selectin protein. This leads to recurrent bacterial infections due to the impaired ability of immune cells to adhere to and eliminate infected cells.
LAD-2 is also associated with severe growth retardation and intellectual disability. The condition can be diagnosed through genetic testing, which identifies mutations in the SLC22A1 gene that encodes for the E-selectin protein. Treatment typically involves antibiotics to prevent recurrent infections and supportive care to address the growth and developmental issues associated with the disorder.

Ovarian dysgenesis type 1 is a genetic condition that affects the development of ovaries. It is an autosomal recessive disorder, which means it requires the presence of two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) for the person to develop the disease. The condition is characterized by underdevelopment or malfunction of the ovaries, leading to infertility and other health problems. It has a material basis in genetic inheritance, specifically due to mutations in the FSHR gene on chromosome 2p16.

Ovarian dysgenesis 2, also known as BMP15 deficiency, is a type of x-linked monogenic disease that affects the development of female reproductive organs. It is characterized by the underdevelopment or absence of ovaries and uterus in affected individuals. This condition occurs due to mutations in the BMP15 gene, which is located on the Xp11 chromosome.

Ovarian dysgenesis 3, also known as 46 XX gonadal dysgenesis, is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It refers to a condition where the ovaries of an individual with this genetic disorder fail to develop properly. This can lead to a range of health problems and physical abnormalities in affected individuals.

Ovarian dysgenesis 3 is caused by a mutation in the PSMC3IP gene, which is located on chromosome 17q12-q21. The gene encodes a protein that plays an important role in the development and function of reproductive organs. When this protein is not produced correctly due to the genetic mutation, it can disrupt normal ovarian development and lead to the various health problems associated with this condition.

It is important for individuals who suspect they may have a genetic disorder such as ovarian dysgenesis 3 to consult with a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment options. Early detection and intervention can help manage the symptoms and improve outcomes for affected individuals.

Ovarian dysgenesis 4, also known as 46 XX gonadal dysgenesis, is a type of autosomal recessive disease where the ovaries fail to develop properly during fetal development. This condition is caused by a homozygous mutation in the MCM9 gene located on chromosome 6q22. It is characterized by the presence of two X chromosomes (46 XX) and underdevelopment of the ovaries, which can result in infertility or other reproductive issues.

Ovarian dysgenesis 5, also known as 46 XX gonadal dysgenesis, is a type of autosomal recessive disease that occurs due to the presence of a homozygous mutation in the SOHLH1 gene on chromosome 9q34. This condition affects the development of female reproductive organs and can lead to infertility or other health problems. It is important for individuals with this condition to seek medical attention and genetic counseling to understand their risk factors and make informed decisions about their reproductive plans.

Ovarian dysgenesis 6, also known as gonadal dysgenesis 6 or simply ovarian dysgenesis, is a type of autosomal recessive disease where the development of the ovaries in individuals with this condition is affected. It is characterized by underdevelopment of the ovaries due to a genetic mutation. The genetic mutation that causes this disorder is located on chromosome 12q15 and involves a gene called NUP107. The disease is also known as 46, XX gonadal dysgenesis, which refers to the fact that individuals with this condition have two X chromosomes (46, XX), but the ovaries develop abnormally.

Ovarian dysgenesis 7, also known as MRPS22-CDG (Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation), is a rare genetic disorder caused by mutations in the MRPS22 gene located on chromosome 3q23. It primarily affects females and is characterized by underdevelopment or malformation of the ovaries, leading to infertility or other reproductive issues.
It's a type of autosomal recessive disease, which means that to develop the condition, an individual must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent).
The disorder is caused by a deficiency in the enzyme mitochondrial ribosomal protein S22 (MRPS22), which is involved in the process of glycosylation. Glycosylation is the addition of sugars to proteins, and it plays an essential role in the proper functioning of cells and organs. In individuals with MRPS22-CDG, this process is disrupted, leading to the developmental problems and symptoms associated with ovarian dysgenesis 7.
It's important to note that while genetic counseling can help identify those at risk for inherited conditions like these, it should be done by a qualified professional.

Ovarian dysgenesis 8, also known as 46 XX gonadal dysgenesis, is a type of autosomal dominant disease where the ovaries do not develop properly in a female foetus. It is caused by a mutation in the ESR2 gene on chromosome 14q23. The condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutations and can lead to infertility or other reproductive issues.

gm1 gangliosidosis type 2 is a type of gm1 gangliosidosis that is characterized by slowly progressive generalized neurodegeneration and mild skeletal changes. It typically affects children between the ages of 7 months and 3 years old. The condition is also known as juvenile GM1 gangliosidosis.

GM1 gangliosidosis type 1 is a genetic disorder that affects the nervous system and causes severe symptoms such as rapid psychomotor deterioration, hepatosplenomegaly, facial dysmorphism, macular cherry-red spots, skeletal dysplasia, and early death. It is characterized by a lack of GM1 ganglioside, which is an important component of the nervous system. This disorder is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that a person needs to inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the disease. It typically affects infants and young children, with symptoms usually appearing within 6 months of birth. Treatment options are limited and mainly focus on managing symptoms and providing supportive care to improve quality of life.

Multiple congenital anomalies hypotonia seizures syndrome (MCAHS) is a type of physical disorder that is characterized by severe global developmental delay, hypotonia, and early-onset seizures. It is associated with multiple cardiac, genitourinary, and gastrointestinal congenital anomalies.

parkinson's disease 22 is a type of autosomal dominant inheritance, characterized by late onset symptoms and a genetic basis in the coiled-coil-helix-coiled-coil-helix domain containing 2 gene located on chromosome 7p11.2. It is also known as autosomal dominant Parkinson's disease 22.

Cornelia de Lange Syndrome (CDLS) is a rare genetic disorder that affects multiple organ systems, including the face, hands, and feet. It is characterized by specific facial features such as large ears, widely spaced eyes, and a prominent chin. Other common features include short stature, joint hypermobility, and developmental delays. CDLS is caused by mutations in the NIPBL gene on chromosome 5p13.

Cornelia de Lange Syndrome type 2 (CdLS2) is a rare genetic disorder caused by mutations in the SMC1A gene, which is located on the X chromosome at position Xp11. It is an example of an X-linked dominant disease, meaning that it affects males more severely than females due to the presence of only one functional copy of the gene (XY0).
Symptoms of CdLS2 can include developmental delays, distinct facial features, and a range of physical abnormalities. The syndrome is typically diagnosed in early childhood and can affect multiple organ systems in the body. Treatment for CdLS2 focuses on managing symptoms and improving quality of life.

Cornelia de Lange syndrome 3, also known as CDLS3, is a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a wide range of physical and developmental issues in affected individuals. These can include short stature, craniofacial abnormalities, hand and foot deformities, hip dysplasia, and spinal problems. The syndrome is caused by mutations in the SMC3 gene on chromosome 10q25.2. It is important to note that Cornelia de Lange syndrome 3 can also be associated with midline brain defects, which can further impact the development of affected individuals.

Cornelia de Lange Syndrome (CDLS) is a rare genetic disorder that affects multiple organ systems. It is characterized by severe developmental delays, distinct facial features, and a wide range of other symptoms. CDLS 4, specifically, is an autosomal dominant form of the condition, which means it can be passed down through family members with little to no risk to the affected individual. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the RAD21 gene on chromosome 8q24. CDLS 4 can also have midline brain defects, but not all individuals with CDLS will have this feature.

Cornelia de Lange Syndrome type 5 (CdLS) is a rare genetic disorder that affects multiple organ systems, including the face, limbs, heart, gastrointestinal tract, and skeletal system. It is caused by mutations in the HDAC8 gene on chromosome Xq13, which encodes the histone deacetylase 8 protein. The condition is inherited in an X-linked dominant manner, meaning that a single copy of the mutated gene (in this case, located on the X chromosome) is sufficient to cause the disorder in males and females.
CdLS is characterized by severe developmental delay, growth retardation, distinctive facial features, and various congenital anomalies. The severity of symptoms can vary greatly among affected individuals.
There is no cure for CdLS, but early intervention and multidisciplinary care can help manage the condition and improve quality of life. Treatment may include special education programs, physical therapy, speech therapy, occupational therapy, and medical management as needed.

Epidermolysis bullosa simplex localized type is a form of epidermolysis bullosa simplex, which is a group of genetic skin disorders that can cause the skin to become fragile and prone to blistering. EBSI localized type typically starts in childhood or adulthood and affects the hands and feet, while other types may affect the entire body. It is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, which means that a single copy of the mutated gene is sufficient to cause the condition. Treatment options depend on the severity of the disease but may include wound care, protection from UV light, and physical therapy.

Epidermolysis bullosa simplex (EBS) is a group of genetic skin disorders that primarily affect the skin's ability to hold its components together. EBS can manifest in different forms, including the generalized type, which is characterized by widespread blisters that appear at birth or in early infancy. The term "epidermolysis bullosa simplex" refers specifically to this group of disorders, and it is not uncommon for people to use the terms interchangeably. However, it's important to note that there are other types of EBS, such as the epidermolysis bullosa simplex Koebner type, which may have slightly different characteristics or causes. Overall, EBS is a complex condition with various presentations and challenges for those affected by it.

Meier-Gorlin Syndrome 1, also known as Type I Meier-Gorlin Syndrome, is a type of autosomal recessive disorder. It is characterized by the presence of multiple epiphyseal dysplasia (abnormal growth of the ends of bones) and other skeletal abnormalities. The syndrome is caused by mutations in the ORC1 gene, which is located on chromosome 1p32. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ORC1 gene.

Meier-Gorlin Syndrome type 2 is a genetic disorder that results from mutations in the ORC4 gene. It is an autosomal recessive condition, which means that to develop the disease, a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene, one from each parent. The syndrome affects development and can cause growth abnormalities, such as short stature, microcephaly, and characteristic facial features. It is important for those affected by this condition to work with healthcare professionals to manage their symptoms and ensure proper growth and development.

Meier-Gorlin Syndrome 3, also known as MGS III or Meier-Gorlin syndrome type 3, is a genetic disorder that affects the development of bones and teeth. It is caused by mutations in the ORC6 gene, which is located on chromosome 16q11.
MGS III belongs to a group of disorders known as Meier-Gorlin Syndrome, which are characterized by abnormalities affecting bone development and growth. These disorders can cause a wide range of skeletal problems, including short stature, premature closure of certain growth plates, and deformities in the facial bones.
In addition to these skeletal abnormalities, MGS III may also be associated with other health issues, such as dental problems (including missing teeth or jaw abnormalities), hearing loss, and intellectual disability. However, not all individuals with MGS III will experience these additional health problems, and the severity of symptoms can vary greatly among affected individuals.
Overall, Meier-Gorlin Syndrome 3 is a rare genetic condition that can have significant impacts on a person's growth, development, and overall health. If you or someone you know has been diagnosed with MGS III, it is important to work closely with a team of medical professionals to manage the condition and ensure proper care and support.

Meier-Gorlin Syndrome Type 4 is a genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to break down certain fats, leading to a build-up of fat in the liver and other organs. It is caused by mutations in the CDT1 gene, which is located on chromosome 16q24. The condition can cause severe liver damage, as well as problems with growth and development. Symptoms may include abnormal bone development, short stature, and jaundice. Meier-Gorlin Syndrome Type 4 is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition.

Meier-Gorlin syndrome type 5, also known as MGS5, is a rare form of autosomal recessive disorder. It is characterized by the presence of multiple cysts on the ossicles (ear bones) which can cause hearing loss, deafness or impaired balance in severe cases. The condition is inherited from both parents and typically affects children.

Meier Gorlin Syndrome 6, also known as Meier-Gorlin syndrome, is a type of autosomal dominant genetic disorder. It is characterized by the presence of multiple cysts in both ovaries and sometimes in other organs such as the breasts, lungs, and liver. The condition is caused by mutations in the GMNN gene, which is located on chromosome 6p22.

Meier-Gorlin syndrome type 7, also known as MGS7, is an autosomal recessive disorder characterized by the presence of multiple epiphyseal dysplasia and craniosynostosis. It is caused by mutations in the CDC45 gene located on chromosome 22q11. The condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CDC45 gene.

Papa syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disorder characterized by the presence of several skin and joint issues. It is caused by mutations in the PSTPIP1 gene located on chromosome 15q24. The symptoms of Papa syndrome include pyoderma gangrenosum, pyogenic arthritis, acne, and suppurative hidradenitis. These symptoms are often present from a young age and can be debilitating if not properly managed. While there is no cure for the condition, treatment options such as medication and surgery may help to alleviate the symptoms.

Polyagglutination syndrome, also known as galactosyltransferase deficiency, is a rare hematopoietic system disease characterized by red blood cells that agglutinate upon exposure to almost all human sera, but not to autologous serum or the sera of newborns. It is caused by a somatic mutation in the C1GALT1C1 gene on chromosome Xq24.

Lung non-small cell carcinoma (NSCLC) is a type of lung cancer that is characterized by the lack of evidence of squamous differentiation. It is one of the two main types of NSCLC, the other being small cell lung cancer. Non-squamous NSCLC is also known as lung adenocarcinoma when it originates in the gland cells of the lungs, or lung bronchioloalveolar carcinoma when it originates in the bronchioles and alveoli of the lungs. It can be further subdivided into several subtypes based on the characteristics of the tumor, such as the presence of certain genetic mutations or the location of the tumor within the lung.

Thyroid gland anaplastic carcinoma is a type of thyroid gland carcinoma characterized by the presence of undifferentiated cells. It is also known as anaplastic thyroid cancer, and it is considered to be one of the most aggressive forms of thyroid cancer. It is important to note that this type of cancer can grow quickly and spread to other parts of the body, making early detection and treatment crucial for the best possible outcome.

Adult-onset leukoencephalopathy with axonal spheroids and pigmented glia (ALAS/P) is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the brain. It is characterized by progressive dementia, apraxia, apathy, impaired balance, parkinsonism, spasticity, and epilepsy. The disease has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the CSF1R gene on chromosome 5q32. It is also known as hereditary diffuse leukoencephalopathy with spheroids (HDL-CS1).

Adenocarcinoma is a type of cancer that develops from glandular epithelial cells. Adenocarcinoma can occur in various organs and tissues throughout the body, including the thyroid gland. When adenocarcinoma occurs in the thyroid gland, it is referred to as thyroid gland adenocarcinoma or thyroid carcinoma. Thyroid gland adenocarcinoma is a type of malignant neoplasm that originates from the epithelial cells of the thyroid gland. It is important to note that there are different subtypes of thyroid gland adenocarcinoma, and each has unique features and treatment requirements.

Differentiated thyroid gland carcinoma, also known as papillary thyroid cancer or thyroid gland adenocarcinoma, is a type of thyroid gland cancer that arises from follicular cells. It is the most common form of thyroid gland cancer and is characterized by a well-differentiated tumor with clear cells that are arranged in small, rounded clusters (nests). The tumor often spreads to the lymph nodes, but can also spread to other parts of the body. It is typically treated with surgery and radioactive iodine therapy, and the prognosis is generally good for patients with early-stage disease.

Bronchiectasis 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, where the bronchi in the lung become widened and damaged. It is caused by mutation in the gene encoding the beta subunit of the epithelial sodium channel on chromosome 16p12.

Bronchiectasis 2 is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the lungs. It is characterized by the enlargement of the airways, which can lead to chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). Bronchiectasis 2 has a material basis in mutations in the gene encoding the alpha subunit of the epithelial sodium channel.

Bronchiectasis 3 is a type of autosomal dominant disease. Bronchiectasis is the medical condition characterized by the dilation or widening of the airways in the lungs, usually due to chronic inflammation and mucus accumulation. Autosomal dominant means that the disease has been inherited from one parent who passed it on through their genes. It is not necessary for the affected person to have a specific number of copies of the gene; they just need one working copy. This type of bronchiectasis is caused by mutations in the gene encoding the gamma subunit of the epithelial sodium channel, which is responsible for regulating fluid balance and electrolyte transport in the lungs.

Granular corneal dystrophy 1, also known as Groenouw type I, is a type of granular corneal dystrophy characterized by recurrent erosions and gray crumb-like opacification in the cornea. It is caused by an autosomal dominant inheritance of heterozygous mutation of the transforming growth factor beta-induced gene located on chromosome 5q31.1, which encodes keratoepithelin. This leads to increased protein deposition and disruption of the corneal surface, resulting in progressive vision loss later in life as deposits move into the central vision.

That is correct. Dedifferentiated liposarcoma is a type of liposarcoma that has undergone a transformation, resulting in the development of high-grade cells from previously low-grade tissue. It is characterized by its aggressive behavior and poor prognosis compared to other types of liposarcoma.

SMARCA4-deficient sarcoma of the thorax, also known as SMARCA4-DTS, is a type of thoracic cancer characterized by poorly differentiated neoplasms with epithelioid/rhabdoid cells organized in a solid pattern. It has a material basis in alterations in the switch/sucrose nonfermenting complex (SNC) and is associated with BRG1-associated factors (BAF chromatin remodeling complex).

Carney Stratakis Syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects multiple organ systems. It is characterized by the presence of paragangliomas, which are non-cancerous tumors that arise from specialized cells called chromaffin cells. These tumors can be found in various locations throughout the body, including the head and neck, lungs, and gastrointestinal tract. Additionally, individuals with Carney Stratakis Syndrome may also develop gastrointestinal stromal sarcoma, a type of cancer that arises from cells called mesenchymal cells. The disorder is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that a mutation in one copy of the gene is sufficient to cause the disorder. Myxofibrosarcoma is a type of sarcoma that arises from the soft tissue and is characterized by the presence of spindle-shaped cells, cellular pleomorphism, thin-walled blood vessels, fibrous septa, and myxoid stroma. It has the exact synonym fibromyxoid sarcoma.

hypermanganesemia with dystonia 1, also known as a rare genetic disorder called manganese-dependent superoxide dismutase (MnSOD) deficiency, is caused by mutations in the SLC30A10 gene on chromosome 1q41. Hypermanganesemia with dystonia 2 is a condition characterized by the loss of motor milestones in the first years of life, primarily as a result of a homozygous mutation in the SLC39A14 gene on chromosome 8p21.

Sweeney-Cox syndrome is a rare genetic disorder characterized by a range of physical abnormalities. It is caused by mutations in the TWIST1 gene, which is located on chromosome 7 at position p21. The condition is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that having one copy of the mutated gene is enough to cause the disorder.

People with Sweeney-Cox syndrome may have distinctive facial features, such as hypertelorism (widely spaced eyes), a cleft palate or velopharyngeal insufficiency, low-set cupped ears, and deficiencies of the eyelids and facial bones. They may also experience speech difficulties due to the cleft palate or other structural abnormalities in the mouth and throat area.

Overall, Sweeney-Cox syndrome can have a significant impact on an individual's quality of life, as many of its physical symptoms can make it challenging to perform daily activities and social interactions. However, with appropriate medical care and support, people with this condition can lead fulfilling lives.

Pepinsky Syndrome, also known as Cerebellar Ataxia Type 16, is a rare genetic disorder that affects the cerebellum of the brain. The primary symptom is severe ataxia (loss of coordination), which can lead to problems with balance, gait, and speech. Other symptoms may include dystonia (involuntary muscle contractions), tremors, and a wide range of cognitive and behavioral issues. Galactosialidosis is a rare genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to break down certain types of carbohydrates. It is caused by a deficiency of two enzymes, beta-galactosidase and neuraminidase, which are necessary for the proper metabolism of galactose and sialic acid. The condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, meaning that both copies of the gene must be abnormal for the disorder to develop.

Hyperprolinemia type 1 is a genetic disorder that results from mutations in the proline dehydrogenase gene, which is located on chromosome 22q11. Hyperprolinemia type 2 is a condition where the body has too much proline, which can cause muscle weakness and cramping. It is caused by a mutation in the pyrroline-5-carboxylate dehydrogenase gene on chromosome 1p36. It can be inherited in an autosomal recessive manner.

Hyper IgM Syndrome is a rare genetic disorder characterized by an abnormal production of IgM antibodies and a deficiency in the production of other types of immunoglobulins, such as IgA, IgG, and IgE. Nonalcoholic fatty liver (NAFL) is a metabolic dysfunction-associated steatotic liver disease characterized by the absence of inflammation and hepatocyte injury in the form of hepatocyte ballooning.

Noonan syndrome with multiple lentigines, also known as LEOPARD syndrome, is a genetic disorder characterized by short stature, hypertelorism (widely spaced eyes), and lentigines (moles) on the neck, face, upper arms, and legs. Congenital disorder of glycosylation type Ia (CDG-IA) is a rare genetic disease that affects the way certain proteins are made and function in the body. Congenital disorder of glycosylation IP, also known as CDG type I, is a rare genetic disorder that affects the way certain proteins are processed in the body. It is caused by mutations in the ALG11 gene, which is located on chromosome 13q14. This disorder can cause various symptoms such as facial dysmorphism (microcephaly, high forehead, low posterior hairline, strabismus), hypotonia, failure to thrive, intractable seizures, developmental delay, persistent vomiting and gastric bleeding. It is an autosomal recessive disorder, meaning that it requires the presence of two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) for an individual to develop the condition.

Congenital disorder of glycosylation IQ, also known as congenital disorder of glycosylation 1q, is a rare genetic disorder characterized by a highly variable phenotype that presents with severe visual impairment, variable ocular anomalies (such as optic nerve hypoplasia/atrophy, iris and optic nerve coloboma, congenital cataract, glaucoma), intellectual disability, cerebellar abnormalities, nystagmus, hypotonia, ataxia, and/or ichthyosiform skin lesions. The disorder has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SRD5A3 gene located on chromosome 4q12. It is an autosomal recessive disease, which means that to develop the disorder, an individual must inherit two copies of the defective gene (one from each parent).

Congenital disorder of glycosylation IR (CDG-IR) is a type of congenital disorder of glycosylation that is characterized by failure to thrive, developmental delay, hypotonia, strabismus and hepatic dysfunction. It has a material basis in compound heterozygous mutations in the DDOST gene on chromosome 1p36.

Congenital disorder of glycosylation 1t, also known as alpha-dystroglycanopathy or Fukuyama congenital disorder, is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of muscle and bone tissue. It is caused by mutations in the PGM1 gene on chromosome 1p31, which leads to decreased phosphoglucomutase 1 enzyme activity. This can result in a wide range of clinical manifestations, including bifid uvula and cleft palate at birth, growth delays, hepatopathy, myopathy, intermittent hypoglycemia, dilated cardiomyopathy, and/or cardiac arrest. Symptoms can vary widely among affected individuals and may be more severe in males than females. Treatment options are limited, but early intervention and supportive care can improve outcomes for those affected by this disorder.

Congenital disorder of glycosylation I, also known as CDG-IU, is a rare genetic condition that affects the way certain proteins are assembled in the body. It is an autosomal recessive disorder, which means it is inherited from both parents and can cause severe developmental delays, physical abnormalities, and health problems.
People with CDG-IU have a high risk of developing respiratory distress and severe hypotonia at birth, as well as other issues such as seizures, myopathic facies, craniofacial dysmorphism, flexion contractures, and elevated creatine kinase levels.
CDG-IU is caused by mutations in the DPM2 gene on chromosome 9q34. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the DPM2 gene.
It's worth noting that CDG-IU is also known as Congenital disorder of glycosylation 1u.

Congenital disorder of glycosylation IW, also known as CDG IW or congenital disorder of glycosylation type I, is a rare genetic disorder that affects the way certain proteins are modified. These modifications are important for normal development and functioning of cells in the body.

CDG IW is caused by mutations in the STT3A gene on chromosome 11q24. This gene provides instructions for making an enzyme called starch branching enzyme I, which is involved in the modification process. When the STT3A gene does not work correctly due to a mutation, this leads to problems with glycosylation, which can cause a range of symptoms and health issues.

People with CDG IW may experience developmental delay, intellectual disability, failure to thrive (difficulty gaining weight and growing at a normal rate), hypotonia (low muscle tone), and seizures. The severity of symptoms can vary widely among affected individuals and can change over time.

While CDG IW is rare, it is important for those who have the condition to receive proper medical care and support to manage their symptoms effectively.

Congenital disorder of glycosylation IX (CDG-IX) is a rare genetic disorder that affects the way certain proteins are properly folded and function. It is one of the many types of congenital disorders of glycosylation, which are caused by mutations in genes that encode for enzymes involved in the process of glycosylation. CDG-IX specifically results from a deficiency or absence of an enzyme called alpha-dystroglycan, which is important for the proper development and maintenance of the nervous system and muscle. Symptoms of CDG-IX can include intrauterine growth retardation, microcephaly, failure to thrive, developmental delay, intellectual disability, hypotonia, seizures, optic nerve atrophy, and respiratory difficulties. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition.

Congenital disorder of glycosylation Iy (CDG Iy) is a type of congenital disorder of glycosylation that has both genetic and environmental factors as its causes. It is characterized by neurologic abnormalities, facial dysmorphism, feeding problems, failure to thrive, gastrointestinal abnormalities, strabismus, and has a material basis in hemizygous mutation in the SSR4 gene on chromosome Xq28.

Larsen-like syndrome, B3GAT3 type is a rare genetic disorder that affects multiple systems of the body. It is characterized by laxity, dislocations and contractures of the joints, short stature, foot deformities (such as clubfeet), broad tips of fingers and toes, a short neck, dysmorphic facial features (including hypertelorism, downslanting palpebral fissures, upturned nose with anteverted nares, high arched palate), and various cardiac malformations. The disorder is caused by homozygous mutation in the B3GAT3 gene on chromosome 11q12. It has a recessive inheritance pattern, which means that an individual must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the disorder.

Spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia Genevieve type is a type of autosomal recessive disease, characterized by infantile-onset severe developmental delay and skeletal dysplasia, including short stature, premature carpal ossification, platyspondyly, longitudinal metaphyseal striations, and small epiphyses. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the NANS gene on chromosome 9q22.

Polygenic diseases are a type of genetic disorder that is characterized by the interaction of multiple genes, each contributing to the development or progression of the disease. These diseases can be inherited in a polygenic manner, meaning that they are the result of the interaction of multiple genes at different loci (locations) on the genome. Examples of polygenic diseases include heart disease, diabetes, and certain types of cancer. It is important to note that while these diseases can have a strong genetic component, other environmental and lifestyle factors also play a role in their development and progression.

digenic disease is a type of polygenic disease, which means it is influenced by the interaction of multiple genes. One important aspect of digenic diseases is that they require the presence of pathogenic variants in two different genes to express the phenotype.
An example of a digenic disease is cystic fibrosis, which is caused by mutations in both copies of the F508del gene and other genes that contribute to the disease.
Digenic diseases can also be referred to as autosomal recessive disorders, where an individual must inherit two copies of a pathogenic variant to develop the disease.

3-Methylcrotonyl-CoA carboxylase deficiency is a rare genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to break down certain amino acids. Specifically, it affects the enzyme 3-methylcrotonyl-CoA carboxylase, which is responsible for converting 3-methylcrotonyl-CoA into succinyl-CoA. This deficiency can lead to a build-up of 3-methylcrotonyl-CoA and other related compounds in the body, which can cause a range of symptoms such as lethargy, irritability, and developmental delays.

3-Methylcrotonyl-CoA carboxylase deficiency is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a child must inherit two copies of the gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition. It is also known as 3-methylcrotonyl-CoA carboxylase (MCC) deficiency or M3 metabolism disorder.

Diagnosis of 3-methylcrotonyl-CoA carboxylase deficiency typically involves a combination of clinical evaluation, laboratory tests, and genetic testing. Treatment options may include dietary changes, supplements, and enzyme replacement therapy in severe cases. It is important to work with a healthcare professional who can provide guidance on managing this condition effectively.

3-Methylcrotonyl coa carboxylase 2 deficiency is a type of 3-methylcrotonyl coa carboxylase deficiency.
It is also known as 3-Methylcrotonyl-CoA carboxylase deficiency that has_material_basis_in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding the beta subunit of 3-methylcrotonyl-CoA carboxylase on chromosome 5q13.

Hyperekplexia 4, also known as congenital hyperexcitability type 4 or CHX4, is a rare genetic disorder that affects muscle tone and movement. It is caused by mutations in the ATPase gene on chromosome 10q23. The condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the disorder.
Hyperekplexia 4 leads to extreme hypertonia, stiffness, and rigidity in the muscles, causing difficulty in movement and coordination. It primarily affects the lower limbs, but can also affect other parts of the body. The condition is usually diagnosed in infancy or early childhood and can lead to severe disability if not properly managed. Treatment options include physical therapy, medications, and surgery, depending on the severity of the condition.

Hypotrichosis 14 is a type of hypotrichosis characterized by sparse to absent lanugo-like scalp hair, sparse and brittle eyebrows, and sparse eyelashes and body hair. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the LSS gene on chromosome 21q22.

Wolfram syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects multiple systems in the body. It is caused by a mutation in the Wolfram gene, which is located on the X chromosome. There are two forms of Wolfram syndrome: the mitochondrial form and the nuclear form. The mitochondrial form is caused by a mutation in the mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA), while the nuclear form is caused by a mutation in one of the autosomal chromosomes.
Wolfram syndrome primarily affects the endocrine system, causing insulin-dependent diabetes mellitus and insipidus, optic atrophy, deafness, and other neurological symptoms. It can also affect other systems in the body, such as the kidneys, liver, and gastrointestinal system.
There is no cure for Wolfram syndrome, but with proper medical care, individuals with this condition can manage their symptoms and live a relatively normal life. Treatment may include insulin therapy for diabetes management, vision therapy to improve vision loss, and other supportive care measures as needed.

Autosomal dominant Wolfram syndrome is a type of Wolfram syndrome, which is characterized by congenital progressive hearing impairment, diabetes mellitus, and optic atrophy. It has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance of a heterozygous mutation in the WFS1 gene on chromosome 4p16.

Van Maldergem Syndrome 1, also known as Van Maldergem syndrome type 1 or VMS1, is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the homozygous mutation of the DCHS1 gene on chromosome 11p15. This genetic abnormality leads to dysfunction in the metabolism of cholesterol and its derivatives, resulting in a range of developmental and physiological issues in affected individuals.
It is essential for those diagnosed with VMS1 to work closely with healthcare professionals experienced in managing these types of disorders to develop effective treatment plans and support systems tailored to their unique needs.

Van Maldergem Syndrome Type 2, also known as VMS2, is a genetic disorder characterized by the presence of an abnormality in the FAT4 gene located on chromosome 4q28. This leads to various developmental and clinical issues, which can include craniosynostosis, hypertelorism (widened distance between the eyes), dental problems, hearing loss, intellectual disability, and short stature. It is important for patients with VMS2 to receive proper medical care and support to manage their symptoms effectively.
Congenital myasthenic syndrome 22 is a type of autosomal recessive disease.
agammaglobulinemia 5 is a type of agammaglobulinemia that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the LRRC8A gene on chromosome 9q34.

Klippel-Feil syndrome (KFS) is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of the skeletal system, characterized by abnormal bone growth and fusion. KFS is caused by mutations in specific genes responsible for controlling bone growth. There are three types of KFS: type I, II, and III.
Klippel-Feil syndrome 1 (KFS1) is a type of autosomal dominant disorder, which means that if one parent has the gene mutation, there is a 50% chance that their child will inherit the condition. The GDF6 gene on chromosome 8q22 is responsible for causing KFS1.
KFS1 affects the cervical spine (neck), leading to fusion of the vertebrae and potential issues like limited mobility, pain, and impaired breathing. Additionally, other skeletal abnormalities may occur in some cases. However, with proper medical care and support, individuals with KFS can lead a relatively normal life despite their condition.

Klippel-Feil syndrome 2 (KFS2) is a type of KFS that results from autosomal recessive inheritance. It occurs when an individual has a homozygous mutation in the MEOX1 gene, which is located on chromosome 17q21. This genetic condition causes severe neck and spine deformities, as well as other physical abnormalities.

Klippel-Feil syndrome (KFS) is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of the bones in the neck and spine. It is caused by mutations in the GDF3 gene, which is located on chromosome 12p13. The severity of symptoms can vary greatly among individuals with KFS, but it typically includes shortened cervical vertebrae, fusion of the cervical vertebrae, and limited neck movement. In some cases, there may also be other skeletal abnormalities present. KFS is usually diagnosed in childhood and is inherited in an autosomal dominant pattern.

Klippel-Feil syndrome (KFS) is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of bones in the spine and neck. It is caused by mutations in the MYO18B gene on chromosome 22q12, which is responsible for encoding the non-muscle myosin IIA protein. This protein plays a role in the development, maintenance, and repair of muscles and other tissues.

KFS usually presents with characteristic physical features such as short stature, a prominent neck, and an abnormal curvature of the spine (kyphosis). Other common symptoms include limited mobility, weakness, and pain in the affected areas. In some cases, KFS can also be associated with other health issues, such as developmental delays or heart problems.

Diagnosis of KFS is typically made through a combination of physical examination, X-ray imaging, and genetic testing. Treatment options for KFS are focused on managing symptoms and may include medications, physical therapy, and surgery in severe cases. While there is no cure for KFS, early diagnosis and treatment can help improve the quality of life for those affected by this disorder.

Orofacial cleft 6 refers to a type of orofacial cleft that has a material basis in variation in an enhancer of the IRF6 gene on chromosome 1q32. It is a form of autosomal dominant disease, which means it can be passed down through families and tends to occur more frequently in individuals with a family history of the condition.

Hyper IgE Recurrent Infection Syndrome 2 (HIRES2) is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which means that it is inherited from one's parents when both of them have the necessary gene mutation. This condition is part of a larger group of disorders known as hyper IgE syndromes, characterized by high levels of IgE antibodies in the blood.

In HIRES2, the excessive production and activation of mast cells are particularly pronounced. Mast cells are a type of white blood cell that play an important role in protecting the body against parasites and foreign substances. However, when there is too much IgE present in the system, these mast cells can become overactive, leading to chronic inflammation, recurrent infections, and tissue damage.

The DOCK8 gene, located on chromosome 9p24, has been identified as a key contributor to HIRES2. Mutations in this gene can lead to the dysfunction or complete loss of an important protein involved in regulating mast cell activation. As a result, excessive IgE production and the subsequent inflammation that comes with it are more likely to occur, ultimately leading to the characteristic symptoms of HIRES2.

In summary, Hyper IgE Recurrent Infection Syndrome 2 (HIRES2) is an autosomal recessive disease characterized by high levels of IgE antibodies and chronic inflammation caused by dysfunctional mast cells. This condition is linked to mutations in the DOCK8 gene on chromosome 9p24, which affects the regulation of mast cell activation.

Hyper-IgE Recurrent Infection Syndrome 3 (HIRES3) is a type of autosomal recessive disease that results from a homozygous mutation in the ZNF341 gene on chromosome 20q11. It belongs to the larger category of hyper IgE syndromes, which are characterized by elevated levels of IgE antibodies and recurrent infections. HIRES3 is a rare disorder that affects the immune system and increases susceptibility to various types of infections. It is important for individuals with this condition to work closely with healthcare professionals to manage their symptoms and prevent complications.

Hyper IgE Syndrome Type 4 (HIES4) is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is one of the types within the larger category of Hyper Immunity E Coli Enterotoxigenic (HIEC). HIES4 is characterized by recurrent infections, particularly with Escherichia coli bacteria. The condition is caused by mutations in the IL6ST gene on chromosome 5q11.

Kleefstra Syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that primarily affects the development of the brain and spinal cord. It is characterized by a combination of intellectual disability, severe speech and language delays, and weak muscle tone. The specific cause of Kleefstra Syndrome is not yet fully understood, but it is believed to be due to mutations in the KLEIFRA gene on chromosome 4.
Symptoms of Kleefstra Syndrome usually become evident during early childhood and can include developmental delays in motor skills, social interactions, and problem-solving abilities. In addition, individuals with Kleefstra Syndrome may have difficulty speaking or using language and may experience muscle weakness, which can impact their overall mobility and quality of life.
While there is no cure for Kleefstra Syndrome, early intervention and specialized therapies can help individuals manage their symptoms and improve their daily functioning. These may include physical therapy, speech and language therapy, occupational therapy, and educational support to help them reach their full potential.

Kleefstra Syndrome 2 is a genetic disorder that affects brain development and causes intellectual disability. It is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that a single copy of the faulty gene is enough to cause the disorder. The disorder is characterized by delayed psychomotor development, mild dysmorphic features, and variable intellectual disability. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the KMT2C gene on chromosome 7q36.
Coronavirus is a type of virus that causes the infectious disease known as COVID-19. COVID-19 is a respiratory illness caused by the SARS-CoV-2 virus, which is a member of the coronavirus family.

Covid-19 is a type of infectious disease caused by the SARS-CoV-2 virus. It can be transmitted through various means such as droplet spread, close contact with an infected individual, and airborne transmission. Common symptoms of Covid-19 include fever, cough, and shortness of breath. The disease has been identified as a coronavirus infectious disease that is characterized by these symptoms and has a material basis in SARS-CoV-2. It has also been referred to as 2019 Novel Coronavirus (2019-nCoV), 2019-nCoV infection, COVID-19, SARS-CoV-2 infection, Wuhan coronavirus infection, and Wuhan seafood market pneumonia virus infection.

Germ cell benign neoplasm refers to a type of non-cancerous tumor that originates from germ cells. These cells are responsible for the development and growth of an individual's reproductive organs, such as ovaries or testes.

While germ cell benign neoplasms are not cancerous, they can still cause issues if they grow too large or press on nearby organs or nerves. Treatment options may include surgery, radiation therapy, or hormone therapy, depending on the specific type of germ cell benign neoplasm and its location in the body. It is essential to consult with a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment recommendations.

A benign teratoma is a type of germ cell neoplasm that has a specific definition. It is characterized by the fact that it derives from mature tissue elements or a limited amount of immature tissue elements. This type of tumor is generally considered to be benign and does not have the potential to become cancerous.

Ankylosing spondylitis (AS) is a type of arthritis that primarily affects the spine and sacroiliac joints. It occurs when the body's immune system attacks the lining of the spinal joints, causing inflammation and pain. Ankylosing spondylitis 1 refers to a specific subtype of AS that is associated with a variation in the HLA-B27 allele on chromosome 6p21.3. This subtype is characterized by a strong family history, early age of onset, and more severe disease compared to other subtypes. Treatment for ankylosing spondylitis typically includes medications, physical therapy, and in some cases, surgery.

Ankylosing spondylitis 2, also known as HLA-B27-associated spondyloarthropathy (SpA), is a subtype of the autoimmune disease ankylosing spondylitis. It is characterized by inflammation and fusion of the sacroiliac joints, leading to chronic pain and stiffness in the lower back and hips. HLA-B27 is a genetic marker that is strongly associated with the development of this subtype of ankylosing spondylitis. It is also known as B27AS or AS2.

Ankylosing spondylitis (AS) is a type of inflammatory arthritis that primarily affects the spine, but can also involve other joints and connective tissues. Ankylosing spondylitis 3, specifically, refers to a subtype of AS that has a variation in the HLA-B gene on chromosome 2q36.1-q36.3. This genetic variation is linked to an increased risk for developing AS and can influence the severity and progression of the disease.
Anterior segment dysgenesis 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease.

Anterior segment dysgenesis 2 is a medical condition that affects the anterior segment of the eye, which includes the cornea and iris. It is caused by mutations in the FOXE3 gene on chromosome 1p36. The condition can lead to abnormal development of the eye and vision problems. Anterior segment dysgenesis 2 is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition.

Anterior segment dysgenesis 3 is a type of autosomal dominant disease. Anterior segment dysgenesis 3 is a condition where the anterior segment of the eye does not develop properly during embryonic development. This can lead to abnormalities in the shape and size of the cornea, which can cause vision problems. Anterior segment dysgenesis 3 is caused by mutations in the FOXC1 gene on chromosome 6p25.

Anterior segment dysgenesis 4, also known as Peters' anomaly, is a type of congenital eye defect that affects the development of the anterior segment of the eye. It is characterized by abnormal growth or underdevelopment of the iris, ciliary body, and other structures in the front part of the eye. This condition can cause various complications, such as glaucoma, cataracts, and poor vision. Anterior segment dysgenesis 4 is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, which means that a person with a single copy of the mutated gene has a 50% chance of developing the condition. The genetic variation responsible for anterior segment dysgenesis 4 is a heterozygous mutation in the PITX2 gene on chromosome 4q25.
Anterior segment dysgenesis type 5 is a specific form of anterior segment dysgenesis characterized by heterozygous mutation in the PAX6 gene on chromosome 11p13.

Anterior segment dysgenesis 6, also known as Anterior Segment Dysgenesis Type VI, is a rare genetic condition that is caused by a compound heterozygous mutation in the CYP1B1 gene on chromosome 2p22. This condition affects the development of the anterior segment of the eye, which includes the iris and ciliary body.

Anterior segment dysgenesis is a group of genetic disorders that can cause various problems with the development or functioning of the structures in the eye's anterior segment. It can lead to abnormalities such as misplaced or missing irises, cloudy or opaque lenses, and irregular pupils. In some cases, it can also cause glaucoma, which is a condition where the pressure within the eye becomes too high, potentially leading to vision loss if left untreated.

Treatment for Anterior Segment Dysgenesis 6 typically involves regular monitoring by an ophthalmologist and may include medications or surgery to manage any complications that arise. It is important for individuals with this condition to work closely with their healthcare provider to develop an appropriate treatment plan based on their specific needs and circumstances.

If you have been diagnosed with Anterior Segment Dysgenesis 6, it is essential to follow your healthcare provider's recommendations and attend regular appointments to ensure proper management of the condition. Additionally, you may want to consider joining a support group or speaking with other individuals who have similar experiences to gain a better understanding of the condition and learn how to cope with its challenges.
Anterior segment dysgenesis 7 is a type of autosomal recessive disease.

Anterior segment dysgenesis 8 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which means that it is inherited through the autosome (non-sex chromosome) and only expresses itself when two copies of the gene are present. This condition affects the development of the anterior segment of the eye and can cause vision problems if left untreated. It is caused by mutations in the CPAMD8 gene located on chromosome 19p13, which encodes for a protein involved in the development and maintenance of the ciliary body.

oculocutaneous albinism type vi is a form of oculocutaneous albinism. Oculocutaneous albinism type vi has the following definition: an oculocutaneous albinism that has its underlying cause in an autosomal recessive mutation of the SLC24A5 gene on chromosome 15q21.1.

nephroma is a type of kidney benign neoplasm. It refers to the intersection of two different conditions: a kidney cortex disease and a benign neoplasm. Nephroma is also known as a benign nephrooma or renal oncocytoma, which are both considered synonyms for the same condition.

Nephroma primarily affects the kidney cortex, and while it may not be cancerous, it can cause significant health problems if left untreated. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect that you have nephroma, as prompt treatment can help manage symptoms and prevent complications. In conclusion, nephroma is a kidney cortex disease characterized by the presence of benign tumors or neoplasms in the renal cortex.

Kidney cortex disease is a specific type of kidney disease that occurs when the outer part of the kidney, known as the cortex, becomes damaged or diseased. This can affect the function of the kidneys and potentially lead to complications such as high blood pressure, anemia, and electrolyte imbalances. It is important for those with kidney cortex disease to work closely with their healthcare provider to manage their condition effectively and prevent further damage.
Lymph node benign neoplasm is a type of immune system organ benign neoplasm.

Lymph node carcinoma is a type of cancer that starts in the lymph nodes, which are part of the immune system. It can also be referred to as lymphoma, although this term specifically refers to a broader group of cancers that affect the lymphatic system. Lymph node carcinoma can develop from epithelial cells, which line the surfaces and cavities of organs and glands in the body. When these cells become abnormal and begin to grow uncontrollably, they can form a tumor in the lymph nodes.

An auditory system benign neoplasm is a type of non-cancerous tumor that develops within the auditory system, which includes the outer, middle, and inner ear. This type of growth can cause issues with hearing, balance, or both depending on its location and size. It's important to note that benign neoplasms are not cancerous, but they still require medical attention to prevent complications such as infection or further growth. Treatment options may include surgery, radiation therapy, or a combination of both, depending on the specific type of benign neoplasm and its location within the auditory system.

Familial glucocorticoid deficiency (FGD) is a rare genetic condition that affects the adrenal gland's ability to produce enough cortisol. Cortisol, also known as hydrocortisone, is a hormone that helps regulate blood pressure, blood sugar levels, and the body's immune response. People with FGD may experience low blood sugar (hypoglycemia), low blood pressure (hypotension), and a weakened immune system. They often need to take steroid medications to replace the missing cortisol.

Glucocorticoid Deficiency 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, where the deficiency occurs due to mutations in the gene that encodes the melanocortin-2 receptor (also known as the adrenocorticotropin receptor), which is located on chromosome 18p11. It can be inherited through homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations, and it is also referred to as familial glucocorticoid deficiency.
peroxisome biogenesis disorder 2b is a type of autosomal recessive disease that has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the PEX5 gene on chromosome 12p13.3.

heimler syndrome 1 is a medical condition that affects the peroxisomes in the body. It is caused by mutations in the PEX1 gene on chromosome 7q21, and it can cause hearing loss, enamel hypoplasia of the permanent teeth, nail defects, and other problems. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition.

Peroxisomal biogenesis disorder 4C (Heimler syndrome 2) is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of the peroxisome, a structures found in many cells that play an important role in metabolism. It is caused by mutations in the PEX6 gene on chromosome 6p21. The disorder can lead to problems with hearing and vision, enamel hypoplasia (a condition characterized by abnormal development of teeth), nail defects, and other developmental issues. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the gene (one from each parent) to develop the disorder.
Severe congenital neutropenia 1 is a type of severe congenital neutropenia that has material basis in heterozygous mutation in the neutrophil elastase gene on chromosome 19p13.

Corticosterone methyloxidase deficiency 1, also known as aldosterone synthase deficiency, is a rare genetic disorder that affects the adrenal gland. It is caused by a mutation in the CYP11B1 gene, which leads to an imbalance in the production of corticosterone and aldosterone. This can result in excessive sodium levels in the urine and insufficient potassium levels, which can cause a range of health problems such as high blood pressure, electrolyte imbalances, and dehydration.

Symptoms of corticosterone methyloxidase deficiency 1 typically appear in the first few weeks of life and may include low blood pressure, vomiting, diarrhea, and rapid weight loss. In some cases, the condition can be treated with hormone replacement therapy to restore normal levels of corticosterone and aldosterone. However, it is essential to seek medical attention if you suspect that you or a loved one may have this condition, as early diagnosis and treatment are crucial for managing symptoms and preventing long-term health complications.

Alopecia Mental Retardation Syndrome (AMRS) is a rare genetic disorder that affects the scalp, eyebrows, eyelashes, axillary hair, and pubic hair. It is characterized by sparse or absent hair growth in these areas, along with mild to severe intellectual disability. The condition can be inherited through a person's genes or caused by certain genetic mutations. Treatment for AMRS typically focuses on managing the symptoms and improving quality of life. This may include using specialized shampoos to help remove dead skin cells, using gentle hair care products to reduce breakage, and providing emotional support and education to help individuals with AMRS cope with their condition.

Alopecia mental retardation syndrome 1, also known as AHGDS (Alopecia Hair Growth Deficiency Syndrome), is a rare genetic disorder that affects the hair and brain development. It is an autosomal recessive disorder, which means that it requires the inheritance of two copies of the faulty gene, one from each parent. The disease is caused by mutations in the AHSG (Amino Acid Metabolism, Hair Growth and Development) gene located on chromosome 3q27.
Alopecia mental retardation syndrome 1 symptoms typically include sparse hair growth or complete baldness, slow brain development, intellectual disability, and abnormal facial features. The disease can also affect the endocrine system, causing problems such as irregular menstrual cycles in women and low levels of testosterone in males.
Treatment for Alopecia mental retardation syndrome 1 is symptomatic and supportive, focusing on managing hair loss, addressing developmental issues, and improving quality of life. There is no cure for the condition, but early diagnosis and intervention can help improve outcomes for affected individuals.

Alopecia-mental retardation syndrome 2 (AMR2) is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by hair loss and mental retardation. The condition has a genetic basis, specifically in variations in chromosome 3q26.2-q26.31.

B-cell acute lymphoblastic leukemia (ALL) is a type of cancer that affects the white blood cells called B cells. In this disease, too many immature B cell lymphoblasts are found in the bone marrow and the blood. As a result, the body is unable to produce enough normal blood cells to function properly.

ALL can be classified into different subtypes based on the characteristics of the cancer cells. One such subtype is B-cell acute lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma (B-ALL), which is characterized by too many immature B cell lymphoblasts in the blood and bone marrow. Another subtype is precursor B lymphoblastic lymphoma/leukemia, which refers to a group of cancers that are similar to B-cell ALL but may also include some other types of lymphoma.

Treatment for B-ALL typically involves chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and sometimes bone marrow transplantation. The specific treatment plan will depend on the stage of the cancer, the patient's age and overall health, and other factors. It is important to work with a healthcare professional to determine the best course of treatment for each individual case.

Elshay Waters Syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects various aspects of a person's development. The primary symptoms include brachycephaly (a short, broad head), facial asymmetry, marked hypertelorism (wide separation between the eyes), proptosis (excessive outward displacement of the eyeball), blepharochalasis (excessive tearing and thickening of the eyelids), midface hypoplasia (underdeveloped midface area), a broad nose with a concave nasal ridge, and prognathism (an underbite).

Additionally, individuals with Elshay Waters Syndrome may experience radicular dentin dysplasia, which results in obliterated pulp chambers, apical translucent cysts, recurrent infections, and early tooth loss. They may also have vertebral fusions at C2-C3, and moderate mental retardation is often present as well.

It's important to note that Elshay Waters Syndrome is a complex disorder with multiple symptoms and potential complications. If you or someone you know may be experiencing these symptoms, it's crucial to consult with a medical professional for proper diagnosis and treatment options.

Fazio-Londe disease is a type of autosomal recessive disorder characterized by progressive bulbar palsy, motor, sensory and cranial neuronopathy. Nanophthalmos is a type of microphthalmia, which is a condition where one or both eyes are very small. Optic disc anomalies with retinal and/or macular dystrophy is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by abnormalities in the optic nerve head, retina, and/or macula. B-lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma with BCR-ABL1 is a type of cancer that affects the blood and bone marrow. B-lymphoblastic leukemia lymphoma (B-ALL) is a type of cancer that affects the white blood cells called lymphocytes. In B-ALL, there are too many immature lymphoblasts in the bone marrow and blood. 45 x 46 xy mixed gonadal dysgenesis is a type of mixed gonadal dysgenesis. otospondylomegaepiphyseal dysplasia autosomal dominant is a condition that is caused by mutations in the COL11A2 gene, which is located on the long (q) arm of chromosome 9. mucolipidosis III gamma is a type of autosomal recessive disorder that affects the body's ability to properly metabolize certain types of fats. It is characterized by short stature, skeletal abnormalities, cardiomegaly, and developmental delay.
