It is important to note that while genetic testing can help diagnose EDS, it should only be done by qualified professionals and in accordance with established guidelines to ensure accuracy and patient privacy.
Overall, EDS is a complex condition that requires ongoing management and support from healthcare professionals to address the various symptoms and complications associated with this disorder.

Brittle cornea syndrome 2 (BCS2) is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the cornea, which is the clear, dome-shaped surface at the front of the eye. It is part of the Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome (EDS) family of disorders and is characterized by its weakness and fragility, resulting in a higher risk of developing corneal problems such as thinning and cracking. BCS2 has a genetic basis, with mutations in the PRDM5 gene on chromosome 4q27 being responsible for the condition.

Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome (EDS) is a group of genetic disorders that affect the body's connective tissue, which provides strength and flexibility to various body structures. The Cardiac Valvular type of EDS is characterized by severe problems with heart valves, which can lead to mitral valve prolapse or other related complications. This type of EDS is caused by mutations in the COL1A2 gene on chromosome 7q21.

Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome (Classic Like 1) is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the connective tissue in the body. It is characterized by hyperextensible skin, hypermobile joints, and tissue fragility. The condition has a material basis in an omozygous or heterozygous mutation in the tenascin-XB gene (TNXB) on chromosome 6p21.

Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome Classical Type 2 (EDS2) is a type of autosomal recessive disorder that affects the connective tissues in the body. It is characterized by severe joint and skin laxity, osteoporosis involving the hips and spine, osteoarthritis, soft redundant skin that can be acrogeria-like, delayed wound healing with abnormal atrophic scarring, and shoulder, hip, knee, and ankle dislocations. The condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the AEBP1 gene on chromosome 7p13.

Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome (EDS) is a group of inherited disorders that affect the body's connective tissue, which provides strength and flexibility to various organs and tissues. EDS can cause severe skin fragility, joint hypermobility, muscle weakness, and other symptoms.
There are several types of EDS, including classical, hypermobile, cardiac-valvular, arthrochalgia, and dermatosparaxis. Each type has its own specific set of features and severity. EDS is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the faulty gene to develop the condition.
Dermatosparaxis is one of the types of EDS that is characterized by severe skin fragility, sagging, redundant skin, and other symptoms. It has a material basis in mutations in the ADAMTS2 gene on chromosome 5q35.

Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome, Kyphoscoliotic Type 1 is a type of Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome characterized by severe muscle hypotonia at birth, generalized joint laxity, scoliosis at birth, and scleral fragility and rupture of the ocular globe. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding lysyl hydroxylase (PLOD1) on chromosome 1p36.

Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome, Kyphoscoliotic Type 2 (EDS2) is a rare genetic disorder that affects the connective tissue in the body. It is caused by mutations in the FKBP14 gene on chromosome 7p15. The disorder leads to severe muscle hypotonia, progressive scoliosis, joint hypermobility, and skin that is easily bruised or stretched. Additionally, people with EDS2 may also experience hearing loss, myopathy, and other health problems. It is an autosomal recessive disorder, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition.

Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome (EDS) is a group of genetic disorders that affect connective tissue in the body. There are several types of EDS, and they can cause various symptoms depending on which type a person has.
One of the types of EDS is EDS Musculocontractural Type 1, which is also known as Beals Syndrome. This type of EDS affects connective tissue in the joints, skin, and other organs. People with this condition may experience muscle and bone problems, as well as severe pain. They may also have difficulty moving their joints and skin that is easily bruisable and hyperextensible.
In addition to these symptoms, people with EDS Musculocontractural Type 1 may also have craniofacial dysmorphism, which means they may have unusual facial features. They may also have congenital contractures of the thumbs and fingers, clubfeet, severe kyphoscoliosis, muscular hypotonia, wrinkled palms, joint hypermobility, and ocular involvement.
It is important to note that EDS Muscolocontractural Type 1 is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner. This means that a person must inherit two copies of the gene for the condition to develop. If someone has only one copy of the gene, they are a carrier and can pass the gene on to their children, but they typically do not have symptoms themselves.
If you or someone you know is experiencing symptoms of EDS Muscolocontractural Type 1, it is important to speak with a medical professional for proper diagnosis and treatment.

Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome (EDS) is a group of genetic disorders that affect the body's connective tissue. It causes hypermobility, skin that is easily stretched, and joint problems. There are several types of EDS, including the musculocontractural type which is caused by mutations in the DSE gene on chromosome 6q22. This type of EDS can cause severe muscle weakness and developmental delays.

Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome, Spondylodysplastic Type 1 (EDS-SD1) is a type of EDS characterized by short stature, developmental anomalies in the forearm bones and elbow, bowing of extremities, and other classic features such as joint laxity, skin hyperextensibility, and poor wound healing. It has a genetic basis, specifically due to mutations in the B4GALT7 gene on chromosome 5q35.

Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome (EDS) is a group of genetic disorders that affect the connective tissue in the body. EDS primarily affects the skin, joints, and blood vessels. It can cause a wide range of symptoms, including chronic pain, fatigue, and joint instability. There are several types of EDS, each with its own specific set of features.

EDS type 3, also known as hypermobile EDS, is characterized by extreme joint mobility, skin that is easily stretched, and a predisposition to developing anxiety or depression. People with this type of EDS may also have other physical symptoms such as chronic pain, fatigue, and organ dysfunction.

The cause of EDS is a mutation in one of the genes that provide instructions for making the proteins that make up the collagen. Collagen is a protein found in connective tissue, which gives structure to skin, bones, muscles, and other body structures. When there is a mutation in a gene that provides instructions for making collagen, it can cause the collagen to be unstable or defective, leading to weakness or instability in connective tissues.

There is no cure for EDS, but treatment can help manage symptoms and improve quality of life. This may include physical therapy, pain management, and medication to reduce anxiety or depression. It's important to work with a healthcare provider to develop an individualized treatment plan based on your specific needs and symptoms.

Libman-Sacks endocarditis is a type of autoimmune disease that affects the cardiovascular system. It is characterized by the presence of Libman-Sacks vegetations and can be commonly found in patients with systemic lupus erythematosus. This condition can also be complicated with embolic cerebrovascular disease, but it has a unique definition as an endocarditis that is characterized by abnormal immunoglobulin levels. The exact synonym for Libman-Sacks endocarditis is Libmann-Sachs, and it is commonly associated with Endocarditis in systemic lupus erythematosus.

Limbic encephalitis is a subtype of encephalitis that affects the limbic system of the brain, which is responsible for various cognitive functions such as memory, emotions, and learning. It is an autoimmune disorder, meaning that the immune system mistakenly attacks healthy cells in the body. In this case, it targets the neurons in the limbic system, causing inflammation and damage to these critical brain structures.

Symptoms of limbic encephalitis can include seizures, psychiatric symptoms such as hallucinations or delusions, and short-term memory loss. The condition is often diagnosed through a combination of imaging studies, such as MRI scans, cerebrospinal fluid analysis, and blood tests to check for elevated levels of certain antibodies. Treatment typically involves the use of immunosuppressive medications to reduce inflammation in the brain and prevent further damage. With appropriate treatment, most people with limbic encephalitis can make a full recovery, although it may take several months or even years for symptoms to resolve completely.

Autoimmune cholangitis, also known as autoimmune hepatitis type 2, is a chronic inflammatory liver disease that affects the bile ducts (also known as biliary tract). It causes the immune system to attack the body's own cells and tissues in the liver and bile ducts. This leads to liver inflammation, damage, and scarring.
Autoimmune cholangitis is often characterized by symptoms such as jaundice, fatigue, abdominal pain, and joint pain. It can also affect other organs in the body, including the skin, eyes, and brain.
Diagnosis of autoimmune cholangitis typically involves a combination of blood tests, imaging studies (such as ultrasound or MRI), and liver biopsy to confirm the presence of inflammation and damage in the liver. Treatment options may include medications such as corticosteroids, immunosuppressants, and anti-inflammatory agents. In some cases, a liver transplant may be necessary.
It is important for individuals with autoimmune cholangitis to work closely with their healthcare provider to develop an appropriate treatment plan and manage any associated symptoms or complications.

Transverse myelitis (TM) is a type of inflammation that affects the spinal cord, specifically in the area where the nerves exit the spinal canal. It results in a band-like sensation across the trunk of the body and can cause various degrees of numbness or tingling below the affected area. TM is often associated with other conditions like multiple sclerosis (MS) and demyelinating disease, but it can also occur as a standalone condition. In some cases, TM may be accompanied by other neurological symptoms such as weakness or loss of coordination in the legs, arms, or both. It is essential to seek medical attention if you suspect that you or someone you know is experiencing symptoms of transverse myelitis, as prompt treatment can help reduce the severity of the condition and improve outcomes.

Antisynthetase syndrome is an autoimmune disease characterized by myositis, arthralgia, Raynaud phenomenon, mechanic hands, interstitial lung disease and serum autoantibodies to aminoacyl transfer RNA synthetases.

Polymyositis is an autoimmune disease that affects the musculoskeletal system. It is characterized by muscle weakness and inflammation, which can impact multiple areas of the body. The exact cause of polymyositis is not yet fully understood; however, it is believed to be triggered by an abnormal immune response that leads to the production of harmful antibodies against healthy tissues within the muscles. Symptoms of polymyositis may include muscle weakness, pain, and fatigue. Diagnosis typically involves a combination of medical history, physical examination, blood tests, and imaging studies. Treatment options for polymyositis may vary depending on the severity of the condition and individual circumstances; however, common treatment approaches may include medications to reduce inflammation and improve muscle function, physical therapy to help restore strength and flexibility, and supportive care to manage symptoms and address any associated complications.

Sweet Syndrome, also known as Acute Febrile Neutrophilic Dermatosis (AFND) or Sweet's syndrome, is a type of skin disease that is characterized by sudden onset of well-defined tender plaques or nodules accompanied by fever, arthralgias, ocular inflammation, headaches, and rarely, oral or genital lesions. It is an allergic disease that typically affects the face and extremities. The exact cause of Sweet Syndrome is not yet known, but it is thought to be triggered by a combination of genetic and environmental factors. Treatment for Sweet Syndrome usually involves corticosteroids and other immunosuppressive medications to reduce inflammation and prevent the spread of the disease.

It is characterized by the presence of raised, itchy skin patches and swelling. In addition to being uncomfortable, chronic urticaria can also cause other problems such as fatigue, joint pain, and difficulty breathing in severe cases.

Chronic inducible urticaria, also known as physician-triggered urticaria or urticaria vasculitis, is a subtype of chronic urticaria that is triggered by physical stimuli such as vibration, pressure, cold, heat, or even medications prescribed by a doctor. It is characterized by persistent itching and the appearance of hives that can last for hours to days. If you have chronic inducible urticaria, it's important to work closely with your healthcare provider to identify triggers, manage symptoms, and develop an effective treatment plan.

Chronic spontaneous urticaria (CSU) is a type of chronic urticaria that occurs independently of any external stimuli. This means that the itching and swelling caused by CSU are not triggered by allergens, physical irritants or other factors in the environment. Instead, people with CSU may experience symptoms such as hives, itchiness, and swollen skin for no apparent reason.

CSU can be a frustrating condition to live with because its cause is often unknown, and there is no cure. However, there are treatments available that can help manage the symptoms and improve quality of life. These may include antihistamines, corticosteroids, or other medications that target specific underlying causes. It's important to consult with a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment options.

Erythema nodosum is a type of panniculitis that is characterized by the sudden onset of painful, erythematous, subcutaneous nodules mainly localized to the pretibial areas. The lesions are usually bilateral and symmetrical, ranging from 1 to 5 cm in diameter.

Keratosis pilaris atrophicans is a skin condition that is characterized by the thickening and dryness of the skin, especially on the upper body. It is an autosomal recessive disease, which means that it is passed down through genes from both parents. The condition can be inherited from either parent, and it is more common in individuals with fair skin.
The symptoms of keratosis pilaris atrophicans include red or brown bumps on the skin, itching, and dryness. These symptoms are caused by the buildup of keratin, a protein that is found in skin cells. The condition can be treated with creams and ointments that help to soften and moisturize the skin, as well as with topical medications that reduce inflammation and itching. In some cases, laser therapy may also be used to treat the condition.

Keratosis pilaris atrophicans faciei is a specific type of keratosis pilaris that affects the eyebrows. It is characterized by the formation of scarring around hair follicles, leading to hair loss in the affected area.

Keratosis follicularis spinulosa decalvans is a type of keratosis pilaris atrophicans characterized by scarring alopecia of the scalp, eyebrows, and axillae. It may also be associated with photophobia and keratoderma.

X-linked keratosis follicularis spinulosa decalvans (KFSD) is a type of keratinization disorder that affects the hair follicles, leading to excessive growth of dead skin cells and eventual hair loss. It's an X-linked recessive genetic disease which means that it's inherited from one's mother, but only if the father is affected as well. The condition has a strong genetic linkage with mutations in the MBTPS2 gene.

Autosomal dominant keratosis follicularis spinulosa decalvans, also known as Androgenetic alopecia, is a type of hair loss that occurs when the hair follicles shrink and stop producing new hair. This condition is characterized by the gradual thinning of hair on the scalp, leading to the development of bald spots. It is believed to be caused by a combination of genetic and hormonal factors, with male pattern baldness being more common than female pattern baldness. Treatment options for autosomal dominant keratosis follicularis spinulosa decalvans may include hair transplant surgery, minoxidil, finasteride, and laser therapy, among others. It is essential to consult a dermatologist or other healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment of this condition.

Atrophoderma vermiculata is a type of keratosis pilaris atrophicans, which is characterized by the presence of erythema and follicular keratotic papules on the cheeks, preauricular area, and forehead. It typically presents in childhood and gradually progresses to atrophy, which has been described as worm-eaten, reticular, or honeycomb.

Fanconi renotubular syndrome 1 is a rare genetic disorder that affects the kidneys and the way they filter waste products from the blood. It is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, which means that a single copy of the altered gene is enough to cause the condition. The genetic alteration is due to a mutation in the GATM gene, located on chromosome 15q21. This disorder can lead to a variety of symptoms, including renal tubular acidosis, hypokalemia, and metabolic alkalosis. Treatment typically focuses on managing symptoms and replacing any lost electrolytes.

fanconi renotubular syndrome 2 is a type of fanconi syndrome, which is characterized by the progressive loss of function in the proximal tubules of the kidney, leading to metabolic acidosis and other health problems. It is caused by a mutation in the SLC34A1 gene on chromosome 5q35. This type of fanconi syndrome can be inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene, one from each parent, to develop the condition.

Fanconi renotubular syndrome 3 is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the kidneys and causes various health issues. It is characterized by rickets, impaired growth, glucosuria, generalized aminoaciduria, phosphaturia, metabolic acidosis, and low molecular weight proteinuria. The condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the EHHADH gene on chromosome 3q27.

Fanconi renotubular syndrome 4 (FRTS4) is a type of autosomal dominant disease that belongs to the Fanconi syndrome family. It is characterized by renal tubular acidosis, renal glycosuria, and metabolic acidosis. This condition is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the HNF4A gene located on chromosome 20q13.

Fanconi renotubular syndrome 5 is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the proximal tubules of the kidneys and can cause progressive kidney disease, pulmonary fibrosis, and other health problems. It has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the NDUFAF6 gene on chromosome 8q22.

Limb-girdle muscular dystrophy 21 is a type of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy.
Limb-girdle muscular dystrophy 21 has the same symptoms as autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2z.
Limb-girdle muscular dystrophy 21 is another name for autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2z.
Limb-girdle muscular dystrophy 21 has the same cause as autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2z.
Limb-girdle muscular dystrophy 21 is a different name for autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2z.

Diffuse gastric cancer is a type of stomach cancer that occurs when malignant cells develop in the lining of the stomach and spread to other parts of the stomach. It is characterized by the presence of signet ring cell changes, which are abnormalities in the shape and size of cells. This type of cancer can be difficult to diagnose and treat, as it often presents with vague symptoms such as nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, and weight loss. It is important for individuals who experience these symptoms to seek medical attention and undergo testing to determine the cause of their symptoms.

Hereditary diffuse gastric cancer is a type of autosomal dominant disease that is characterized by the development of diffuse (signet ring cell) gastric cancer at a young age. It is associated with germline heterozygous mutations of CDH1, MAP3K6 and CTNNA1 genes.

Autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder 72, also known as autosomal recessive mental retardation 72 (ARMRC72), is a type of intellectual and developmental disorder that is caused by a homozygous mutation in the METTL5 gene located on chromosome 2q31. This condition affects the normal functioning of certain enzymes involved in the metabolism of RNA, leading to abnormalities in brain development and cognitive function. Symptoms typically become apparent during early childhood, and can include delayed language and motor skills, low IQ, and problems with social interaction and adaptive behaviors. ARMRC72 is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition.

Erythrokeratodermia variabilis et progressiva 6 is a type of autosomal dominant disease that is characterized by erythematous hyperkeratotic plaques that develop within the first year of life, beginning on distal extremities and progressing to involve the face, wrists, and ankles, with sparing of volar surfaces. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the TRPM4 gene on chromosome 19q13.

Autoimmune myocarditis is a type of autoimmune disease that affects the cardiovascular system. It is characterized by inflammation of the heart muscle, and can cause symptoms such as chest pain and shortness of breath. Autoimmune myocarditis is caused by the immune system attacking the heart muscle, which can lead to damage and potentially life-threatening complications if left untreated. Treatment options may include medications to suppress the immune response, as well as other therapies to manage symptoms and prevent further damage to the heart.

Pyridoxine-dependent epilepsy is a type of autosomal recessive disorder characterized by intractable seizures within the first weeks to months of life that are not controlled with antiepileptic drugs but respond both clinically and electrographically to large daily supplements of pyridoxine.

Early-onset vitamin B6-dependent epilepsy (EPEO1) is a type of epilepsy that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the PLPBP gene on chromosome 8p11.23. It is characterized by abnormalities in vitamin B metabolism and is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern.

Autosomal dominant beta thalassemia is a genetic disorder that is passed down through families, and it affects the body's ability to produce red blood cells. This type of thalassemia is caused by mutations in the HBB gene, which is located on the autosome (non-sex chromosome) and is inherited dominantly. People with autosomal dominant beta thalassemia may experience symptoms such as anemia, fatigue, weakness, yellowing of the skin and eyes, bone deformities, and enlarged liver and spleen. It's important to seek medical attention if you suspect that you or a family member may have this condition.

Beta thalassemia major, also known as Cooley's anemia, is a type of beta thalassemia. Beta thalassemia refers to a group of inherited disorders in which the body produces abnormal or reduced amounts of haemoglobin, the protein that carries oxygen in the red blood cells.
Beta thalassemia major specifically refers to a severe form of the disorder characterized by anemia, enlarged liver and spleen, and other complications before the age of two. It is caused by mutations in the HBB gene on the beta globin chain of haemoglobin, which results in the production of abnormal or non-functional haemoglobin chains.
The exact synonym for beta thalassemia major is Cooley's anemia, named after Dr. John F. Cooley who first described the disorder. It is important to note that while beta thalassemia major can lead to life-threatening complications if left untreated, with early diagnosis and proper medical care, it can be managed effectively.

Beta thalassemia intermedia is a form of thalassemia that is characterized by mild to moderate anemia, slow growth, and bone abnormalities in early childhood or later in life. It is caused by mutations in the HBB gene, which encodes the beta globin protein. These mutations result in the production of abnormal hemoglobin chains that are not properly assembled into functional hemoglobin molecules. The resulting anemia can be managed with blood transfusions and other treatments.

Delta beta thalassemia is a type of autosomal dominant disease where the delta- and beta-globin chains are decreased or absent, resulting in a compensatory increase in fetal gamma-chain synthesis. This leads to a microcytic anemia that is clinically mild.

Thalassemia minor, also known as thalassaemia intermedia, is a genetic disorder that affects the production of haemoglobin in red blood cells. It is caused by mutations in one of the two genes (HBB) that encode for haemoglobin. People with thalassemia minor have low to normal levels of haemoglobin, but their red blood cells are larger than usual due to the presence of large amounts of haem. This can cause mild anaemia and other symptoms such as weakness, fatigue, and enlarged liver and spleen. However, it does not typically cause severe health problems or require regular blood transfusions like thalassemia major.

complete androgen insensitivity syndrome (CAIS) is a specific type of androgen insensitivity syndrome where the individual with this condition has normal chromosomes, typically XY, but is unable to respond to androgens. This results in the development of female external genitalia, breasts, and other characteristics typical of females. However, individuals with CAIS do not have a uterus or the ability to bear offspring due to the lack of receptors for androgens. It is important to note that while they may appear female, they are biologically male.

Partial Androgen Insensitivity Syndrome is a condition where an individual has the genetic makeup of a male (XY), but their body does not respond properly to androgens, resulting in underdeveloped male characteristics. This can include small testes, undescended testicles, and other physical manifestations of masculinization. Despite having a Y chromosome, these individuals are typically raised as girls due to the presence of female genitalia.

Lung sarcomatoid carcinoma is a type of lung cancer that is characterized by the presence of a sarcomatoid component, often associated with giant cell differentiation. It has an aggressive behavior and tends to spread quickly to other parts of the body. The exact synonyms for this type of cancer are Sarcomatoid carcinoma of the lung and pulmonary sarcomatoid carcinoma.

Transient Infantile Liver Failure (TILF) is a rare genetic disorder characterized by liver failure, which can occur in infants or young children. It is caused by mutations in the TRMU gene, which encodes a protein involved in mitochondrial protein translation on chromosome 22q13. The condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that to develop the disease, a child must inherit two copies of the mutated gene, one from each parent. Symptoms typically appear within weeks to months after birth and can include elevated liver enzymes, jaundice, vomiting, coagulopathy, hyperbilirubinemia, and increased serum lactate. Treatment involves managing the symptoms and providing supportive care.

Plasmablastic lymphoma is a subtype of diffuse large B-cell lymphoma (DLBCL), which is characterized by the presence of large neoplastic cells resembling B-immunoblasts that have the immunophenotypic profile of plasma cells. It is typically aggressive and has a poor prognosis compared to other subtypes of DLBCL. Treatment options for Plasmablastic lymphoma may include chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and stem cell transplantation.

Acute erythroid leukemia, also known as acute erythroleukemia or AEoL, is a rare form of leukemia that affects the red blood cells. It is classified under the category of Acute Myeloid Leukemia (AML) and is characterized by an excessive production of immature red blood cells in the bone marrow. These mature red blood cells cannot deliver oxygen properly, which can lead to anemia and other health complications.

The symptoms of acute erythroid leukemia may include fatigue, weakness, shortness of breath, rapid heartbeat, swelling in the legs and feet, and easy bruising or bleeding. Diagnosis is usually made through a bone marrow biopsy and blood tests to determine the presence of an abnormal number of blast cells. Treatment typically involves chemotherapy, radiation therapy, stem cell transplantation, and targeted therapies aimed at eliminating cancerous cells while sparing healthy ones.

It is essential for patients with acute erythroid leukemia to receive timely and appropriate treatment in order to improve their chances of survival and reduce the risk of complications. Early diagnosis and treatment can help slow down or stop the progression of the disease, allowing the patient to lead a more comfortable life.

Benign exocrine pancreas neoplasm refers to a benign (non-cancerous) tumor that forms in the exocrine glandular tissue of the pancreas. The pancreas is a gland located behind the stomach and plays an important role in digestion. This type of neoplasm can cause problems by producing excessive hormones or blocking normal hormone secretion, leading to various health issues. It's important to note that benign exocrine pancreas neoplasm is different from malignant (cancerous) tumors of the pancreas, which are called pancreatic cancer.
Mucinous pancreas adenocarcinoma is a type of malignant tumor that arises from the glandular tissue in the pancreas, which produces mucus.

Brown-Vialetto-Van Laere syndrome 1 (BVVLS) is a type of BVVLS. BVVLS is an autosomal recessive disease that affects both males and females equally. It is caused by mutations in the C20ORF54 gene, which is located on chromosome 20 at position p13.
Brown-Vialetto-Van Laere syndrome 1 (BVVLS) is a type of BVVLS that occurs when an individual has a homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the C20ORF54 gene. This leads to progressive bulbar palsy, which is characterized by weakness and paralysis of the muscles responsible for chewing and swallowing. Additionally, individuals with BVVLS may experience sensorineural deafness, which affects hearing and balance.
Overall, Brown-Vialetto-Van Laere syndrome 1 (BVVLS) is a rare genetic disorder that can have significant impact on an individual's quality of life. With early diagnosis and proper treatment, individuals with BVVLS may be able to manage their symptoms and lead fulfilling lives.

Brown-Vialetto-Van Laere syndrome 2 (BVVL2) is a rare genetic disorder that affects the muscles, particularly those in the face and upper and lower limbs. It causes severe muscle weakness and wasting, leading to respiratory insufficiency and difficulties with speech, swallowing, and mobility. BVVL2 is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that a person needs to have two copies of the gene for the disorder to develop. It's caused by mutations in the SLC52A2 gene located on chromosome 8q24.

Proximal symphalangism I is a type of proximal symphalangism characterized by ankylosis of the proximal interphalangeal joints, carpal and tarsal bone fusion, and in some cases conductive deafness. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the NOG gene on chromosome 17q22.

Proximal symphalangism II, also known as Type 2 proximal symphalangism, is a type of Proximal Symphalangism. It is characterized by the absence of the cuboid bone and a lack of shortness in the first and fifth metacarpal bones. Additionally, it is marked by distal interphalangeal joint fusions and flat feet. This condition is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the GDF5 gene on chromosome 20q11.

Treacher Collins syndrome 1, also known as TCS 1, is a genetic disorder that affects the development of the bones and facial structure. It is caused by a mutation in the TCOF1 gene on chromosome 5q32. This condition can lead to various abnormalities, including underdeveloped or absent outer ear, malformed inner ear, small jaw, and protruding eyes. Treacher Collins syndrome 1 is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, which means that a single copy of the mutated gene is enough to cause the condition. It's important to note that there are other types of Treacher Collins syndrome, but TCS 1 is one of them and has its own specific set of characteristics.

Treacher Collins Syndrome 2 (TCS2) is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of the ears, face, and jaw. It is caused by mutations in the POLR1D gene on chromosome 13q12. The syndrome is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that to develop TCS2, a person must have two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent).

Treacher Collins Syndrome 2 shares some similarities with Treacher Collins Syndrome (TCS), but it is considered a separate and distinct disorder. Like TCS, TCS2 can cause severe ear abnormalities such as underdeveloped or absent ears, known as microtia. However, TCS2 may also affect the jaw, cheekbones, and other facial features.

Individuals with TCS2 may experience various health complications due to the combination of ear and facial abnormalities. These can include hearing loss, speech problems, and dental issues such as misaligned teeth or a small jaw. Proper medical care and interventions are crucial for managing these complications and improving quality of life.

In summary, Treacher Collins Syndrome 2 (TCS2) is a rare genetic disorder characterized by abnormal development of the ears, face, and jaw due to mutations in the POLR1D gene on chromosome 13q12. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern and can cause significant health complications if left untreated.

Treacher Collins Syndrome 3, also known as TCS 3, is a genetic disorder that affects the development of the face and the inner ear. It is one of the three types of Treacher Collins Syndrome, which is an autosomal recessive disorder. Individuals with this condition have underdeveloped facial features, including small or absent ears, a small jaw, and widely spaced eyes. In addition to these physical characteristics, individuals with TCS 3 may also experience hearing loss and other health issues due to the underlying genetic mutation.

Treacher Collins syndrome 4 is a type of Treacher Collins syndrome that is characterized by craniofacial dysmorphisms including downslanting palpebral fissures, malar and mandibular hypoplasia, and microtia and that has_material_basis_in heterozygous mutation in the POLR1B gene on chromosome 2q14.

childhood acute megakaryoblastic leukemia is a form of cancer that affects the bone marrow and blood cells in childhood. It is characterized by the presence of abnormal megakaryocytes, which are large immature blood cells that do not mature into normal platelets. This type of leukemia can be caused by gene mutations or other genetic changes that disrupt the normal functioning of blood cells. Treatment for childhood acute megakaryoblastic leukemia usually involves chemotherapy, bone marrow transplantation, and targeted therapies to destroy cancer cells and promote the growth of healthy cells.

acute basophilic leukemia is a type of acute myeloid leukemia that is characterized by the overproduction of basophils, which are a type of white blood cell. Symptoms may include wheezing, coughing, chest tightness, and shortness of breath. If left untreated, it can lead to long-term respiratory problems and disability. Exercise-induced asthma (EIA) is a form of intrinsic asthma that occurs during or after physical activity. TORCH syndrome, also known as congenital infection syndrome or CIS, is a term used to describe the potential health problems that can occur due to infections that a pregnant woman may have contracted during her pregnancy. The acronym "TORCH" stands for Toxoplasmosis, Rubella, Cytomegalovirus (CMV), and Herpes Simplex virus 1 (HSV-1). These infections can cause a variety of problems for the developing fetus if they occur during pregnancy.

Toxoplasmosis is an infection caused by the Toxoplasma gondii parasite, which can be passed from a mother to her baby through her placenta or breast milk. It can cause problems with the brain and eyes, as well as other organ damage.

Rubella, also known as German measles, is caused by the Rubella virus and can also be passed from a pregnant woman to her baby. It can cause problems with the developing fetus's ears, eyes, heart, and brain.

Cytomegalovirus (CMV) is a member of the family of viruses known as the member of the family of viruses known as the "Lyssaviridae" or "mengleukocytic virus", which also includes the lymphocytic choriomeningitis virus and the Nairovirus. It is primarily spread through saliva, urine, and respiratory droplets, and can cause a variety of problems for the developing fetus if it occurs during pregnancy.

Herpes Simplex virus 1 (HSV-1) is a member of the family of viruses known as the "Viralia", which also includes the Epstein-Barr virus (EBV), and the Kaposi's sarcoma-associated virus (KSHV). It can cause cold sores, and it can be passed from a pregnant woman to her baby during delivery or through breastfeeding.

In conclusion TORCH syndrome is not a specific disease but a term used to describe the potential health problems that can occur due to infections that a pregnant woman may have contracted during her pregnancy, these infections can cause a variety of problems for the developing fetus if they occur during pregnancy.

Vitamin D dependent rickets, also known as metabolic bone disease or osteomalacia, is a condition where the body cannot absorb enough vitamin D to maintain healthy bones. Symptoms typically develop in childhood and include softening and weakening of the bones (osteopenia), which can lead to deformities such as bowing of the legs (hypophosphatemic rickets). In severe cases, it can also result in fractures or other skeletal abnormalities.
Treatment typically involves supplementation with vitamin D and calcium, along with medical supervision to ensure that the child receives appropriate nutrients for proper bone development.

Posterior fossa ependymoma is a type of high-grade ependymoma that refers to the location within the posterior cranial fossa. It is important to note that this specific type of ependymoma is not only located in the supratentorial region but also has a higher grade of malignancy compared to other types of ependymomas.

Supratentorial ependymoma is a type of brain tumor that occurs in the cerebral hemispheres, which are the regions of the brain that control movement and other functions. It is also known as an ependymoma, and it can be further classified into different subtypes based on its cell of origin and location within the brain.
One subtype of supratentorial ependymoma is YAP1-MAMLD1 fusion positive supratentorial ependymoma, which is a type of supratentorial ependymoma that has a material basis in YAP1-MAMLD1 fusion. YAP1-MAMLD1 fusion positive supratentorial ependymoma is a rare form of brain tumor, but it can still cause serious symptoms and complications if left untreated. rela fusion positive ependymoma is a specific type of supratentorial ependymoma that has the presence of a RELA fusion gene. It is also known as C11orf95 fusion-positive supratentorial ependymoma and Supratentorial C11ORF95-RELA fused ependymoma.

Bainbridge-Ropers syndrome, also known as ASXL3-related disorder, is a rare genetic condition characterized by delayed psychomotor development, severe intellectual disability with poor or absent speech, hypotonia, feeding difficulties, poor growth, and dysmorphic facial features. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the ASXL3 gene on chromosome 18q12.

Lipofibromatosis, also known as Schwannomas, is a type of connective tissue cancer. It originates from the sheath surrounding peripheral nerves and has a characteristic appearance with mature adipose tissue and fibrous septae. The genesis of lipofibromatosis involves a mutation in the LMNA gene that leads to an increased production of lipid droplets, causing cell proliferation and tumor formation.

Lipofibromatosis may occur spontaneously or as a result of acquired mutations from various sources such as environmental exposures or inherited genetic factors. The clinical presentation of lipofibromatosis varies depending on the location, size, and number of lesions. Symptoms can include pain, numbness, weakness, or limited mobility due to pressure on the nerve roots.

Diagnosis typically involves imaging techniques such as MRI or CT scans to identify the presence and extent of the tumor. A biopsy may also be performed to confirm the diagnosis and assess the histological features of the lipofibromatosis. Treatment options for lipofibromatosis include surgical excision, radiotherapy, or a combination of both, depending on the size, location, and risk factors associated with the tumor.

In summary, lipofibromatosis is a connective tissue cancer that originates from the sheath surrounding peripheral nerves and has a characteristic appearance with mature adipose tissue and fibrous septae. It is caused by a mutation in the LMNA gene leading to increased lipid droplet production, which results in cell proliferation and tumor formation.
rapidly involuting congenital hemangioma is a type of physical disorder.

Pericytoma with t(7;12)(p22;q13) translocation is a type of perivascular tumor that has material basis in a genetic rearrangement involving the ACTB and GLI1 genes. It is characterized by a perivascular pattern of spindle-to-ovoid cell proliferation, which is a growth pattern involving cells surrounding blood vessels.

That is correct. A solitary fibrous tumor hemangiopericytoma is a type of connective tissue cancer that can affect the lungs, kidneys, and other organs in the body. It is characterized by the presence of a network of thin, elastic fibers, which give it its name "solitary fibrous." Additionally, it may contain blood vessels, which gives it the term "hemangiopericytoma." These tumors are usually slow-growing and can be treated with surgery or other therapies.

Cerebellofaciodental syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects multiple systems of the body. It is caused by mutations in the BRF1 gene on chromosome 14q32. The condition is characterized by delayed development, intellectual disability, abnormal facial and dental findings, and cerebellar hypoplasia.
It is important to note that this disorder is autosomal recessive, meaning that it requires the presence of two copies of the gene (one from each parent) for the individual to develop the condition.

Lung pleomorphic carcinoma is a type of lung cancer that is characterized by the presence of malignant glandular or squamous cells associated with malignant giant and spindle cells. It has a location in the lungs.

oral rhabdomyosarcoma is a rare form of cancer that affects the muscles and connective tissues in the oral cavity. It typically occurs in children and young adults, and can be difficult to treat due to its location in a highly functional area of the body. Treatment options may include surgery, chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and/or targeted therapies. Early detection through regular dental check-ups and awareness of symptoms such as swelling or lumps in the mouth are crucial for effective treatment.

embryonal tumor with multilayered rosettes c19mc altered is a type of cancer that affects the brain and spinal cord. It is characterized by the presence of multilayered rosettes, which are abnormal masses of cells that form within the brain or spinal cord. Additionally, this tumor often has an amplification of the C19MC region on chromosome 19 (19q13.42). Embryonal tumor with multilayered rosettes c19mc altered is also known as ependymoblastoma.

astroblastoma mn1 altered is a type of tumor that affects the brain or spinal cord. It's characterized by astroblastoma-like cells and a rearrangement of the MN1 gene on chromosome 22q. The tumors are high-grade and can be aggressive.
astroblastoma mn1 altered is also known as CNS high-grade neuroepithelial tumors with MN1 alteration.

Central nervous system neuroblastoma is a type of central nervous system germ cell tumor that is characterized by the presence of neuroblastic cells, the absence of ganglion cells, and the absence of prominent Schwannian stroma formation. It arises from the cerebral hemispheres.

The definition of CNS neuroblastoma with FOXR2 activation is a type of central nervous system neuroblastoma that is characterized by the activation of the FOXR2 gene and is composed of small, round cells with hyperchromatic nuclei surrounded by a clear halo. It can also be referred to as CNS NB-FOXR2 or central nervous system neuroblastoma with FOXR2 activation.

Cockayne Syndrome A is a rare genetic disorder characterized by premature aging, short stature, and various developmental abnormalities. It is caused by mutations in the group VIII excision repair cross-complementing gene (ERCC8) located on chromosome 5q11.2. There are two types of Cockayne Syndrome: Type A, which has a homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ERCC8 gene, and Type B, which has a mutation in one of the two non-sense mutated genes (ERCC8L1) on chromosome 5q11.2. The disorder is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern.

Cockayne syndrome B, also known as Cockayne syndrome type 2, is a rare genetic disorder that primarily affects children. It is characterized by severe physical and mental retardation, microcephaly, progressive neurologic and retinal degeneration, skeletal abnormalities, gait defects, and sun sensitivity. Unlike Cockayne syndrome A, which has an increased risk of cancer, individuals with Cockayne syndrome B do not have a higher risk of developing cancer. The disorder is caused by mutations in the group 6 excision repair cross-complementing protein (ERCC6) gene, which is located on chromosome 10q11.

Castration-resistant prostate carcinoma (CRPC) is a type of prostate cancer that continues to grow and spread even after the removal of the testes or other treatments to block androgen production. It is characterized by an increased concentration of androgens, such as testosterone, which helps fuel the growth and spread of the tumor.

CRPC can be treated with hormonal therapies, chemotherapy, and immunotherapy, among other options. In some cases, radiation therapy may also be used to shrink the tumor before other treatments are administered.

It's important for individuals diagnosed with CRPC to work closely with their healthcare providers to develop a personalized treatment plan that takes into account their specific needs and medical history. With appropriate treatment, it is possible to manage the symptoms of CRPC and improve quality of life.

Cerebrooculofacioskeletal syndrome, also known as Cockayne Syndrome, is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the premature aging of an individual due to the gradual degradation of their cells. It primarily affects the brain, eyes, bones and joints, and can lead to severe developmental abnormalities and physical disabilities in affected individuals. The symptoms typically begin in infancy or early childhood, and include microcephaly (abnormally small head size), congenital cataracts, mental retardation, facial dysmorphism, and arthrogryposis. Unfortunately, there is no known cure for this disorder, but researchers continue to work towards finding potential treatments or therapies that may help alleviate some of the symptoms associated with Cockayne Syndrome.

cerebrooculofacioskeletal syndrome 1 is a type of cerebrooculofacioskeletal syndrome that is characterized by a combination of symptoms affecting the brain, eyes, and skeleton. It is caused by mutations in the ERCC6 gene on chromosome 10q11.

Cerebrooculofacioskeletal syndrome 2, also known as Nijmegen Breakage Syndrome (NBS), is a rare genetic disorder that results from compound heterozygous mutations in the DNA repair gene XPD (ERCC2) on chromosome 19q13. This condition affects multiple systems of the body, including the brain, eyes, bones, and skin. It is characterized by a wide range of symptoms such as developmental delays, congenital anomalies, bone fragility, immune system dysfunction, and an increased susceptibility to cancer. The exact cause of NBS is still not fully understood, but researchers believe that it may be related to defects in the DNA repair process or other cellular processes.

Cerebrooculofacioskeletal syndrome 3, also known as CFS-3, is a rare genetic disorder characterized by craniosynostosis (early closure of the skull bones), eye abnormalities, and other skeletal issues. It is caused by mutations in the ERCC5 gene, which is located on chromosome 13q33.

Cerebrooculofacioskeletal syndrome 4, also known as ERCC1-positive osteosarcoma, is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the development of cancer in various tissues, primarily involving bones. It occurs due to mutations in the ERCC1 gene on chromosome 19q13. This condition has a strong genetic component and can be inherited through families. Symptoms may include pain, swelling or limited movement in affected areas, as well as other signs of cancer such as fever, weight loss, and night sweats. Early diagnosis and treatment are crucial for improving the prognosis of this disease.

Histiocytic sarcoma is a type of cancer that affects histiocytes and dendritic cells. It has the definition of being a malignant tumor made up of neoplastic cells that have characteristics similar to those seen in mature histiocytes.

polymicrogyria is a type of brain disease that affects the development of the brain by causing abnormal cortical lamination and an unusual folding pattern of the cerebral cortex. This results in the brain surface being covered with excessive numbers of small folds (gyri).

Bilateral frontal polymicrogyria is a type of polymicrogyria that affects the frontal lobes bilaterally and symmetrically, without involving the areas behind the Sylvius fissure or Rolando sulcus. Bilateral frontoparietal polymicrogyria is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the brain. bilateral perisylvian polymicrogyria is a condition that affects the brain. it is characterized by an abnormal development of the brain and is caused by a genetic mutation. this mutation leads to a reduction in the size of certain brain regions, specifically those in the Sylvian fissure. this condition can cause a range of symptoms including seizures, balance and coordination issues, and cognitive impairment. it is important for people with this condition to receive proper medical care and support to manage their symptoms and improve their quality of life.

Cytochrome P450 oxidoreductase deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the metabolism of steroids. It occurs when there is a deficiency in the enzyme Cytochrome P450 oxidoreductase, which is necessary for the breakdown and elimination of certain steroid hormones. This can lead to the accumulation of steroid metabolites and other steroid hormones, causing a range of symptoms depending on the specific type and severity of the deficiency. It has been linked to genetic mutations in the POR gene, which is located on chromosome 7q11.2.

7q11 23 duplication syndrome is a chromosomal disorder characterized by a duplication of the long arm of chromosome 7 at the q11.23 location. This leads to various developmental and physical abnormalities in affected individuals, including motor, speech and language delays, behavior problems, intellectual disability, low muscle tone (hypotonia), an increased head circumference (macrocephaly), facial dysmorphism, seizures, brain abnormalities, and heart defects such as aortic dilatation. It is also known by the names 7q11.23 microduplication syndrome, William-Beuren region duplication syndrome, and chromosome 7q11.23 duplication syndrome.

Hereditary angioedema type I is a rare genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to regulate blood flow and prevent excessive bleeding. It is caused by mutations in the C1 inhibitor gene (C1NH, SERPING1) on chromosome 11q. The condition can be inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene, one from each parent, to develop the disorder. Symptoms typically begin during childhood and adolescence and may include swelling of the face, extremities, trunk, and genitals, as well as abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, and diarrhea. In some cases, the condition can be life-threatening if left untreated. Treatment options for hereditary angioedema type I include medications to control swelling and prevent future attacks, as well as preventive measures such as carrying an emergency kit with medications in case of a sudden attack.

Hereditary angioedema type III is a form of hereditary angioedema, characterized by recurrent skin swelling, abdominal pain attacks, and potential life-threatening upper airway obstruction. It is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding coagulation factor XII (F12) on chromosome 5q35.

Anauxetic dysplasia is a type of spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia that is characterized by the prenatal onset of extreme short stature, an adult height of less than 85 cm, hypodontia, and mild mental retardation.

46,XX sex reversal 5 is a type of autosomal dominant disease that is characterized by genital virilization in 46,XX individuals and is associated with congenital heart disease and variable somatic anomalies including blepharophimosis-ptosis-epicanthus inversus syndrome and congenital diaphragmatic hernia. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the NR2F2 gene on chromosome 15q26.

Familial Behcet-like Autoinflammatory Syndrome (FBAS) is a type of primary immunodeficiency disease that is characterized by recurring oral and genital ulcers. It is believed to have a genetic basis, with mutations in the TNFAIP3 gene on chromosome 6q23 being one possible cause. It has also been described as A20 haploinsufficiency.

Abdominal obesity metabolic syndrome 4 (AOMS4) is a type of abdominal obesity that is characterized by various health risks, such as hypertension and early-onset coronary artery disease. It is also known to be caused by a heterozygous mutation in the CELA2A gene on chromosome 1p36.

Retinal dystrophy with leukodystrophy is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which means it is passed down through the family and can affect anyone regardless of gender. It also has a material basis in some cases of homozygous mutation in the ACBD5 gene on chromosome 10p12.

Yes, Acute Flaccid Myelitis (AFM) is a type of acute myelitis that refers to the sudden onset of weakness in one or more limbs. This condition affects the spinal cord and can lead to paralysis if not treated promptly. The symptoms typically develop over several hours or days, and may include loss of sensation, muscle weakness, and difficulty moving the affected limbs. It is important to seek medical attention immediately if you suspect you or someone you know may have AFM, as early treatment can significantly improve outcomes.

Agenesis of corpus callosum cardiac ocular and genital syndrome (ACCCOGS) is a rare genetic disorder characterized by a combination of developmental delays, congenital heart defects, craniofacial dysmorphisms, and abnormalities involving the eyes, heart, and genitals. This condition results from mutations in the CDH2 gene located on chromosome 18q12.

Alcoholic ketoacidosis (AKA) is a type of metabolic acidosis, which occurs when the body breaks down fat for energy due to excessive alcohol consumption. During this process, ketones are produced and accumulate in the blood, causing the pH level to become too low. AKA can be life-threatening if not treated promptly, as it can lead to coma and even death. It is important for individuals who have consumed excessive amounts of alcohol to seek medical attention immediately if they experience symptoms such as nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, confusion, or loss of consciousness.

Alopecia is a type of hair loss, and mental retardation syndrome 4 is a condition that affects cognitive functioning. The condition has been linked to a mutation in the LSS gene on chromosome 21q22.
